ov sun = 110\n|Dec sun = 94\n|year sun = 2385\n|source 1 = Slovenian Enivironment Agency (ARSO) <ref name= SEA>{{Cite web |url=http://meteo.arso.gov.si/uploads/probase/www/climate/table/en/by_location/portoroz/climate-normals_71-00_portoroz.pdf\n|title=PORTORO\u017d Climate normals 1971-2000 \n|publisher=ARSO \n|accessdate=September 15, 2012}}</ref> (data for 1971-2000)\n|date=November 2010\n}}\n\n==Arts==\n[[File:Achiam - Hommage aux patriotes tomb\u00e9s pour la libert\u00e9 (Portoroz).JPG|thumb|200px|[[Achiam]] : ''Tribute to the fallen patriots for liberty'' (1963)]]\nPortoro\u017e hosts annual [[Festival of Slovenian Film]] (''Festival slovenskega filma'') with ''Vesna'' awards being awarded for best achievements in Slovenian cinematography.\n\nSince 1961, Portoro\u017e also hosts a contemporary art biennale, the [[International Sculpture Symposium Forma Viva]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.obalne-galerije.si/index.php/si/article/66 |title=Forma Viva |year=2007|accessdate=2012-01-30|ref=harv}}</ref>\nThe works are on display in a sculpture park in the village of [[Se\u010da]].\n\nIn the town houses [[The Rolling Stones Museum]], one of the rare ones in the world.<ref>Wall Street Journal, [http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/print/WSJ_-A001-20121210.pdf Fan Hoping to See Rolling Stones In Slovenia Gets No Satisfaction], 9 December 2012</ref>\n{{clear|right}}\n\n==Sports==\nPortoro\u017e was a home of the [[Banka Koper Slovenia Open]] tennis tournament of [[WTA Tour]] from 2005 to 2010. Since 2013 there is men's [[ATP Challenger Tour|ATP Challenger]] tournament every summer on the same courts of \u0160RC Marina, called [[Tilia Slovenia Open]].\n\nIn 1958, the Portoro\u017e international chess tournament was won by [[Mikhail Tal]]; [[Bobby Fischer]] finished sixth, and was awarded the title of grandmaster at the (then) record age of 15. Tal went on subsequently to win the candidates tournament and the world title of 1960. \n \nPortoro\u017e was host to the [[International Physics Olympiad]] in 1985 and to the [[European Universities Debating Championships]] in 2001.\n\nIn 2008, the new [[Euro-Mediterranean University of Slovenia]] was inaugurated<ref name=harv>{{cite web |url=http://www.emuni.si/en/ |title=Euro-Mediaterranean University in Portoro\u017e \u2014 Official website |accessdate=2012-12-30}}</ref> in collaboration with universities of the EU, the Middle-East and North Africa.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://www.portoroz.si/EN/default.asp Official homepage]\n*[http://www.geopedia.si/Geopedia_en.html#L410_F10123011_T13_b4_x393920.668_y39620.15_s13 Portoro\u017e on Geopedia]\n\n{{Piran}}\n{{Slovenian Riviera}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Portoroz}}\n[[Category:Portoro\u017e| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Municipality of Piran]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Slovenian Riviera]]\n[[Category:Spa towns in Slovenia]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Portoro\u017e\n|other_name             = Portorose\n|image_skyline          = Portoroz_(3956393456).jpg\n|imagesize              = 280px\n|image_caption          = Portoro\u017e in late August 2009\n|pushpin_map            = Slovenia<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Slovenia\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[File:Flag of Slovenia.svg|25px]] [[Slovenia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = Traditional region\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Slovenian Littoral]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Statistical regions of Slovenia|Statistical region]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Coastal\u2013Karst Statistical Region|Coastal\u2013Karst]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Municipalities of Slovenia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Municipality of Piran|Piran]]\n|area_total_km2         =2.97\n|population_as_of               =2002\n|population_total               =2849\n|population_blank1_title        =Ethnicities\n|population_blank2_title        =Religions\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|30|59.88|N|13|34|47.89|E|region:SI|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = 31.2\n|footnotes              = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.si/eng/index.asp |title=Statistical Office of the Republic of Slovenia|accessdate=2012-01-29|ref=harv}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Portoro\u017e''' ({{IPA-sl|p\u0254\u027et\u0254\u02c8\u027eo\u02d0\u0283|pron|Sl-Portoroz.oga}}; {{lang-it|Portorose}}, literally \"Port of Roses\") is a Slovenian Adriatic seaside resort and spa town located in the [[Municipality of Piran]] in southwestern [[Slovenia]]. Its modern development began in the late 19th century with the vogue for the first health resorts. In the early 20th century Portoro\u017e became one of the grandest seaside resorts in [[Adriatic sea|Adriatic]], along with [[Opatija|Abbazia]], [[Lido di Venezia|Lido]] and [[Grado, Friuli-Venezia Giulia|Grado]], then as part of the [[Austrian Littoral]].<ref>http://www.istrabenz.si/slo/turizem/950</ref> It is now one of Slovenia's major tourist areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piran.si/index.php?page=static&item=1&tree_root=1 |title=Piran Municipality site|accessdate=2012-01-31|ref=harv}}</ref> Located in the centre is the [[Kempinski Palace Portoro\u017e|Hotel Palace]], once one of the most important resorts for the [[Austro-Hungarian monarchy]], and currently one of the finest hotels between [[Venice]] and [[Dubrovnik]].<ref>http://www.erevija.com/clanek/1131/Hotel_Palace_-_Portoro\u017e {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304223001/http://www.erevija.com/clanek/1131/Hotel_Palace_-_Portoro%C5%BE |date=2016-03-04 }}</ref>\n\nThe settlement and its surrounding areas are served by [[Portoro\u017e Airport|Portoro\u017e International Airport]] which is located in the nearby village of [[Se\u010dovlje]].\n\n== History ==\nThe history of the settlement is directly connected to that of the neighbouring town of [[Piran]], with [[illyrians|Illyrian]] settlers already living there in the prehistoric era. They were followed by [[Celts|Celtic]] tribes, which were later conquered and annexed by the [[Roman Empire]] in 178 B.C. Archaeological finds suggest that in this period many farms and villas, also named ''villae rusticae'', were built in the area. A large development of the area followed only after the demise of the empire, with enlargement of the number of settlers seeking shelter from attacks by the [[Barbarians]].\n\nIn the 7th century, the area was a part of the [[Byzantine Empire]]. Due to increasing dissatisfaction with the feudal rule, as well as the rising power of the [[Venetian Republic]], the settlement of Pirano signed a trade treaty with [[Venice]], which included a lesser degree of autonomy.\n\n[[File:Postcard of Portoro\u017e 1912 (3).jpg|thumb|left|Portoro\u017e in 1912]]\nOne of the first religious orders who came to this area was the [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictines]]. \nIn the 12th century, the broader region already had four monasteries and even more churches. Among those, one of the oldest was the church of ''Our Lady of the Rosary'', which stood by the bay in the beginnings of the 13th century. Its name was ''Sancta Maria Roxe'' or ''S. Maria delle Rose'', and in 1251 the bay was named by it ''Portus sanctae Mariae de Rosa''.\n\nOne of the most important roles in the history of the settlement was the monastery of Saint Laurence, where the Benedictines healed rheumatic illnesses, ascites and other diseases with concentrated saltwater and saline mud. In 1210, the area was overtaken by the Patriarchy of Aquileia.\n\nIn the 13th century, Pirano entered a brief war from December 1282 to January 1283, in which it was defeated by the Venetian Republic. [[File:Razglednica Portoro\u017ea 1915 (3).jpg|thumb|right|250px|upright|Portoro\u017e's bath in 1915]]\n\nDuring the second Venetian rule, it was, contrary to other towns on the [[Istria]]n peninsula, loyal to Venetian rule, and as such gained special privileges within the republic, which in turn caused the local economy to boom. In 1797, Venetian rule came to a close as the [[Austrian Empire]] took over the area for a brief period until 1806. From 1806 to 1813, the entire Istrian Peninsula became part of the [[Illyrian Provinces]].\n\nA period of economic growth followed during the second Austrian rule, with enlargement of trade and locally important salt pans in nearby [[Lucija]] and [[Se\u010dovlje]]. In the aftermath of the [[World War I|Great War]], the [[Treaty of Rapallo (1920)|Treaty of Rapallo]] determined the Istrian peninsula to be from that point on a part of the [[Kingdom of Italy]].\n\nUnder the royal and then fascist rule, the area found itself amidst economic decline and civil conflicts between the populace and the state. In [[World War II]], the area had not seen much action, although the important industrial hub of Trieste suffered multiple bombings. In the aftermath of the war, the settlement found itself in the [[United Nations]]-administered [[Free Territory of Trieste]]. After the dissolution of the Trieste state it became a part of [[Socialist Federative Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piran-pirano.si/zgodovina/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810055511/http://www.piran-pirano.si/zgodovina/ |archivedate=2014-08-10 }}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n\nThe economy of Portoro\u017e is mainly based on tourism and the [[casino|gambling industry]]. The facilities include a marina,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marinap.si/ |title=Marina Portoro\u017e site|accessdate=2012-12-30|ref=harv}}</ref> numerous sporting facilities and several casinos, along with many hotels and apartment complexes.\n\n===Tourism development===\nIn the second half of the 19th century, the leaders of the [[Pirano]] municipality and local doctors decided to stimulate tourism in the region, by offering health treatment by concentrated salt water and salina mud, and from 1879 onwards Dr. [[Giovanni Lugnano]] the first to offer such treatment to various visitors.\nIn 1885 after several years of successful start of a new branch of industry, constructions of new complexes and villas began, and in 1890 the predecessor of the famous Hotel Palace was built. Among the new settlers were various prominent figures, such as Antonelli, Dragovina, Furian, Frennez, Langer, Rastelli, Reinlaner and Salvetti.\nBecause of the new branch of healthcare treatment that emerged in ''Porto Rose'', the ministry of interior affairs declared the settlement to be a health resort.\nIn 1908 Dr. [[Orazio Pupini]], a prominent Austrian doctor with a noticeable treatment history opened a sanatorium. He was also the main doctor of the Austrian Railways, and a member of the Austrian Doctors\u2019 Association.\nIn 1902 The [[Parenzana]] Railway system was introduced which increased the popularity of the region, but was later dissolved because of decreased interests.[[File:Portoro\u017e 1957.jpg|thumb|left|upright|240px|Palace Hotel in 1957]]\nIn 1909 the era of construction of private villas ended with opening of a much bigger building for standards at the time; the ''Palace Cur Hotel'', later known as [[Palace Hotel, Portoro\u017e|Palace Hotel]]. At the initial opening ceremony, in 1910, the Hotel Palace was already named \u00bbthe most beautiful hotel on the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]] coast\u00ab. The hotel was equipped with the most modern therapeutic accessories, and for the needs of high importance guests a casino was built.\n\nThe thriving community was halted by World War I, and a few years after the war (In which they came under the [[Italy|Italian rule]]) in 1928 they included a new electric therapy among their treatment programmes. In the whole interwar period the settlement was slowly regaining its former glory when World War II  severely crippled it again. The crisis lasted until 1968 when renovations and new constructions under the new entity of [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] began to take place along the whole region. In this time they began to build the settlement's infrastructure with the casino doing the bulk of the investments in reconstructing the [[Portoro\u017e Airport|sports airfield]] in nearby [[Se\u010dovlje]] and building the multi-purpose [[Avditorij Portoro\u017e|auditorium]] in 1972. In 1976 two hotel complexes were constructed in Bernardin, in the following year another was added in the same area.<ref name=\"slovensko-morje.net\">{{cite web|url=http://slovensko-morje.net/index.php?page%3Dnews%26view_news%3D5401 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609043918/http://slovensko-morje.net/index.php?page=news |archivedate=2015-06-09 }}</ref> In the same year they began transforming the [[Lucija, Piran|Lucija saltworks]] into a marina for smaller vessels.<ref name=\"svet24.si\">http://svet24.si/clanek/526942816c4f9/kaj-najbolj-zaznamuje-portoroz</ref>  Since the secession of [[Slovenian War of Independence|Slovenia]] from Yugoslavia, Portoro\u017e became one of the most important tourist sites in the country.<ref>http://www.piran.si/index.php?item=138&page=static</ref>\n<ref>http://www.angelfire.com/biz/mareaslo/zgod.html {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602034758/http://www.angelfire.com/biz/mareaslo/zgod.html |date=2016-06-02 }}</ref>\n\n===Gambling===\nThe first casino to be opened was in Villa San Lorenzo, on 27 July 1913, and was run by the ''Casino des Etrangers'' society. It only lasted briefly for not more than a few months before being shut down.[[File:Portoroz (10) (3955614179).jpg|thumb|right|220px|Hotel Palace in present day]]\nThe industry faded away in the northern Adriatic region, until 1963, when ''Zavod za pospe\u0161evanje turizma'', whose president was Anton Nino Spinelli, proposed a reopening of the casino. The next year the first casino in the [[Socialist Republic of Slovenia]], and the second within [[SFRY|Yugoslavia]] beside the one in [[Opatija]] opened. In 1972, the company moved into the newly built and much larger [[Grand hotel Metropol]], where they employed around 450 people. Having a large budget surplus, they began investing in the settlement's infrastructure.<ref name=\"svet24.si\"/>\nToday there are multiple casinos located in Portoro\u017e, such as [[Casino Riviera]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.casino-riviera.si/pc.asp?xpath%3D%26xpathid%3D%26lang%3Dslo |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714155409/http://www.casino-riviera.si/pc.asp?xpath=&xpathid=&lang=slo |archivedate=2014-07-14 }}</ref> [[Grand Casino (Portoro\u017e)|Grand Casino]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bernardingroup.si/si/metropol-resort/hoteli/grand-hotel-metropol/casino |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140618174650/http://www.bernardingroup.si/si/metropol-resort/hoteli/grand-hotel-metropol/casino |archivedate=2014-06-18 }}</ref> and [[Casino Bernardin]], located in the town's hotel complex of Bernardin.<ref>http://www.casino-bernardin.si/</ref>\n\n===Bernardin===\nBernardin is a tourist complex located in the western part of Portoro\u017e. Its name derives from ''sveti Bernardin'' '[[Bernardino of Siena|Saint Bernardino]]', as the church, now in ruins, was named. Before the construction of multiple complexes, the area was a shipyard for smaller vessels, later moved to the town of [[Izola]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bellatours.si/zanimivosti-na-poti |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701143129/http://bellatours.si/zanimivosti-na-poti |archivedate=2014-07-01 }}</ref>\nIn 1971 [[Emona (company)|Emona]] company from [[Ljubljana]] established [[Hoteli Bernardin]], and began working on building the complex. In 1976 the first two hotels, Bernardin and Vile Park were built, with [[Grand hotel Bernardin|Grand hotel Emona]] following the next year.<ref name=\"slovensko-morje.net\"/>\n\nThe monastery associated with Saint Bernardino's Church, which was built in 1452, was closed in 1806. In 1830, the Austrian military converted the structure into a fortress to guard the Bay of Piran, after which the buildings started to deteriorate.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Oter Goren\u010di\u010d |first1=Mija |title=Srednjeve\u0161ka stavbna dedi\u0161\u010dina avgu\u0161tink, observantov, tretjerednikov in servitov v slovenski Istri |journal=Annales. Series historia et sociologia |date=2013 |volume=23 |issue=1 |page=34 |url=https://www.dlib.si/stream/URN:NBN:SI:doc-QDS84KYE/f8b85be7-7939-4fcd-8963-29611ba56089/PDF |accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n=== Location ===\nPortoro\u017e belongs to the coastal municipality of [[Piran]], located in the southwest of the [[Gulf of Trieste]] (at the northernmost point of the [[Adriatic Sea]]) between the boundaries of [[Italy]] to the north and [[Croatia]] to the south. Part of Portoro\u017e are the streets [[Fiesa, Portoro\u017e|Fiesa]] and [[Pacug]].[[File:Portoro\u017e2.JPG|thumb|right|upright=1.3|Waterfront]]\n\n===Climate===\nPortoro\u017e has [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Cfa'') with cool winters and warm summers. Winters are cool and mild with a January average of {{convert|4.7|C|F|1}} while summers are warm with a July high of {{convert|28.4|C|F|1}} and a low of {{convert|16.5|C|F|1}}. Due to its coastal location, temperatures below {{convert|-10|C|F|1}} or above {{convert|35|C|F|1}} are rare. The average annual precipitation is \n{{convert|931.2|mm|in|0}} which is fairly distributed throughout the year though September and October see a peak in precipitation levels. Portoro\u017e averages 2385 hours of sunshine per year. \n{{Weather box\n|location = Portorose - Portoro\u017e\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 17.6\n|Feb record high C = 22.2\n|Mar record high C = 23.0\n|Apr record high C = 26.3\n|May record high C = 29.5\n|Jun record high C = 35.4\n|Jul record high C = 35.1\n|Aug record high C = 36.9\n|Sep record high C = 32.1\n|Oct record high C = 27.5\n|Nov record high C = 21.0\n|Dec record high C = 19.0\n|year record high C = 36.9\n|Jan high C = 8.6\n|Feb high C = 9.7\n|Mar high C = 13.1\n|Apr high C = 16.8\n|May high C = 21.8\n|Jun high C = 25.5\n|Jul high C = 28.4\n|Aug high C = 28.2\n|Sep high C = 23.9\n|Oct high C = 19.0\n|Nov high C = 13.2\n|Dec high C = 9.7\n|year high C = 18.2\n|Jan mean C = 4.7\n|Feb mean C = 5.1\n|Mar mean C = 8.2\n|Apr mean C = 12.3\n|May mean C = 17.1\n|Jun mean C = 21.0\n|Jul mean C = 23.0\n|Aug mean C = 22.3\n|Sep mean C = 18.2\n|Oct mean C = 14.0\n|Nov mean C = 9.7\n|Dec mean C = 5.9\n|year mean C = 13.5\n|Jan low C = 0.6\n|Feb low C = 0.4\n|Mar low C = 3.1\n|Apr low C = 6.9\n|May low C = 11.0\n|Jun low C = 14.5\n|Jul low C = 16.5\n|Aug low C = 16.3\n|Sep low C = 13.0\n|Oct low C = 9.7\n|Nov low C = 4.7\n|Dec low C = 1.4\n|year low C = 8.2\n|Jan record low C = -12.0\n|Feb record low C = -10.3\n|Mar record low C = -9.7\n|Apr record low C = -2.5\n|May record low C = 2.5\n|Jun record low C = 6.1\n|Jul record low C = 7.6\n|Aug record low C = 7.8\n|Sep record low C = 3.8\n|Oct record low C = 0.2\n|Nov record low C = -5.5\n|Dec record low C = -8.5\n|year record low C = -12.0\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 56.3\n|Feb precipitation mm = 47.1\n|Mar precipitation mm = 61.3\n|Apr precipitation mm = 65.3\n|May precipitation mm = 68.8\n|Jun precipitation mm = 85.8\n|Jul precipitation mm = 57.6\n|Aug precipitation mm = 78.1\n|Sep precipitation mm = 123.8\n|Oct preci