Atlantic Equatorial mode]]\n* [[Mediterranean tropical-like cyclone]]\n* [[Tropical cyclone basins]]\n* [[2006 Central Pacific cyclone]]\n* [[1996 Lake Huron cyclone]]\n* [[Subtropical Cyclone Katie]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|South Atlantic tropical cyclones}}\n* [https://www.marinha.mil.br/chm/ Brazilian Navy Hydrography Center - Marine Meteorological Service] {{in lang|pt}}\n* [http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/G6.html NOAA info on South Atlantic Tropical Cyclones]\n* [http://cimss.ssec.wisc.edu/goes/blog/archives/4659 CIMSS Satellite Blog: \"Another tropical cyclone in the South Atlantic Ocean?\"]\n* [http://www.weathercast.co.uk/weather-news/news/ch/d07e4b2bec38794c4345747482b3cfb2/article/do_hurricanes_form_in_the_south_atlantic.html Meteogroup Weathercast: Do hurricanes form in the South Atlantic?]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FJNNMHoh4-U Satellite animation of the 1991 Angola tropical storm]\n* {{cite journal  |last = Rosa  |first = Marcelo Barbio  |author2 = P. Satyamurty  |author3 = N. J. Ferreira  |author4 = L. T. Silva  |title = A comparative study of intense surface cyclones off the coasts of southeastern Brazil and Mozambique  |journal = Int. J. Climatol.  |volume = 39  |issue = 8  |pages = 3523\u20133542  |date = 2019  |doi = 10.1002/joc.6036 }}\n\n{{South Atlantic tropical cyclone}}\n{{Cyclones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:South Atlantic Tropical Cyclone}}\n[[Category:South Atlantic tropical cyclones| ]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclone meteorology]]\n[[Category:Climate of Brazil]]\n", "name_user": "Da\u00df W\u00f6lf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTheories concerning infrequency of occurrence:c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Atlantic_tropical_cyclone"}
{"title_page": "Bible John", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name=Bible John\n| image     = File:Bible_John_1969_Police_Composite_Sketch.jpg\n| caption   = 1969 [[Facial composite|composite drawing]] of ''Bible John''\n| alt       = Composite drawing of Bible John, created with the assistance of the sister of his last known victim, Helen Puttock\n| victims= 3 \n| locations = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| beginyear= 22 February 1968\n| endyear= 31 October 1969\n| apprehended= Unapprehended \n}}\n\n'''Bible John''' is an unidentified [[serial killer]] who is believed to have murdered three young women between 1968 and 1969 in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lister|first=David Brown, Sean O\u2019Neill and David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bible-john-the-sanctimonious-dancehall-killer-who-vanished-gmfgpwb7j6d|title=\u2018Bible John\u2019 \u2013 the sanctimonious dancehall killer who vanished|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nEach of the victims of Bible John were young [[brunette]] women between the ages of 25 and 32, and all had met their murderer at the [[Barrowland Ballroom]]: a [[dance hall]] and [[music venue]] in the city. The perpetrator has never been identified and the case remains both unsolved and also one of the most extensive [[manhunt (law enforcement)|manhunts]] in Scottish criminal history.<ref>{{cite book|title=Glasgow Almanac: An A-Z of the City and its People|isbn=978-1-906-47625-0|page=112|location=Glasgow|publisher=Neil Wilson Publishing|year=2011|first=Stephen|last=Terry}}</ref>\n\nThe murders committed by Bible John would prove to be the first time in Scotland in which the [[Clerk of the Crown in Chancery|Crown Office]] authorised the publication of a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of an individual suspected of murder for public viewing.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=18}}\n\nThis unidentified serial killer became known as \"Bible John\" due to his having repeatedly quoted from the [[Christian Bible|Bible]] and to have condemned any form of [[adultery]] while in the company of his final victim.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=21}} The known movements and ''[[modus operandi]]'' of convicted serial killer and rapist [[Peter Tobin]] have given rise to suspicions that he may be Bible John.\n\n==First murders==\n===Patricia Docker===\nOn 23 February 1968, the naked body of a 25-year-old [[auxiliary nurse]] named Patricia Docker was found in the doorway of a lock-up garage by a man on his way to work in [[Battlefield, Glasgow|Battlefield, South Glasgow]].<ref name=\"Skelton\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=v-NAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3KYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1709,2603592&dq|title=20 years on, the mystery of Bible John still haunts a city|newspaper=[[Evening Times]]|last=Skelton|first=Douglas|date=10 February 1989|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The location of her body was only yards from her home in Langside Place. Her body bore evidence of extensive [[blunt force trauma]]\u2014particularly to the face and head.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=17}} She had been [[strangulation|strangled]] to death with a strong [[strangling#Ligature strangulation|ligature]], possibly a belt.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=52}} Patricia's handbag, watch, and clothes were missing from the [[crime scene]]. Her clothing was never found,<ref name=\"MacDougall\"/> although her handbag was later recovered from the [[River Cart]] by an [[underwater search and recovery|underwater search unit]],{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}} whereas her watch was recovered from a pool of water close to the scene of her murder.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\">''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 34. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref>\n\nExtensive door-to-door inquiries in the area produced a witness who recalled hearing a female scream, \"Leave me alone!\" the previous evening. Little [[smoking gun|hard evidence]] was discovered at the crime scene. Nonetheless, an ambulanceman who retrieved the body informed investigators the victim had been a nurse who worked at Mearnskirk Hospital in nearby [[Renfrewshire]].<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Consequently, the victim was formally identified by her father the following day.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=191}}\n\nPatricia was a married mother of one but [[family estrangement|estranged]] from her husband.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The night of her murder, she informed her parents she would spend the evening dancing at the Majestic Ballroom in nearby Hope Street, although for unknown reasons, she had chosen to spend the majority of the evening at the Barrowland Ballroom, likely to attend the over-25s night which the Barrowland hosted each Thursday.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> When she failed to return home that evening, her parents assumed she had spent the night with a friend.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petrie|first1=Ewan|title=Bible John: Remembering Notorious Serial Killer's Victims|url=https://stv.tv/news/features/1408716-bible-john-victims-of-notorious-glasgow-serial-killer/|publisher=STV|accessdate=23 July 2018|date=23 February 2018}}</ref> Police inquiries would only determine several days later<ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> that in the late evening, Patricia had left the Majestic Ballroom to attend the Barrowland,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DANCING+WITH+DEATH%3B+CHASING+KILLERS%3A+RETIRED+COP+JOE+JACKSON+ON+THE...-a0186026767|title=Dancing With Death; Chasing Killers|publisher=[[The Free Library]]|website=Daily Record|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> where she had likely encountered her killer.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/><ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[autopsy|postmortem]] conducted by Gilbert Forbes at the [[University of Glasgow Medical School]] confirmed that the cause of death had been strangulation, and that Patricia's body bore no clear evidence of [[sexual assault]].{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=192}}<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\"/> Furthermore, the stage of [[rigor mortis]] upon her body at the time of discovery indicated she had likely died shortly after she had left the Barrowland Ballroom.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=52}} Investigators surmised the perpetrator had likely grabbed Patricia before repeatedly punching her and kicking her in the face as she twice screamed \"Leave me alone!\"<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/> He had then proceeded to [[rape]] Patricia before strangling her to death, and leaving her naked body, with nothing but one shoe nearby, close to the doorway of the lock-up garage at Carmichael Place.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/>\n\n===Jemima McDonald===\nOn Saturday, 16 August 1969, a 32-year-old mother of three named Jemima McDonald also opted to attend the Barrowland Ballroom to spend the evening dancing. Jemima was a regular attendee of the Barrowland, and as per family custom, her sister, Margaret O'Brien, took care of her three children as Jemima attended the Barrowland.<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 35. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> As midnight approached, Jemima was seen by several people in the company of a young, well-dressed and well-spoken man of slim build aged between 25 and 35 and between {{nowrap|6 ft 0 in}} and {{nowrap|6 ft 2 in}} ({{convert|72|and|74|in|cm|disp=out}}) in height.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=195}} This individual had short, dark brown hair with fair streaks,{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=253}} likely spoke with a distinctive [[Glasgow accent|Glaswegian accent]], and occasionally inserted brief Biblical quotations into his conversation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nJemima was seen leaving the Barrowland shortly after midnight on 17 August in the company of this individual, and was last seen walking towards either Main Street or Landressy Street, in the direction of her home, at approximately 12:40&nbsp;a.m.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=195}} The following day, Jemima's sister, Margaret, became concerned when her sister failed to return home. Later the same day, she began hearing local rumours that young children had been seen leaving a derelict [[tenement]] building in MacKeith Street discussing a body in the premises.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> By the Monday morning, Margaret was so concerned that she herself, fearing the worst, walked into the old building. There she discovered her own sister's extensively battered body lying face down, with her shoes and stockings lying beside her.\n\nA postmortem concluded Jemima had been raped and extensively beaten, particularly about the face,<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/> before she had been strangled to death with one of her own stockings. Her murder had occurred approximately 30 hours before her body had been discovered.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Bible John Killer may be Unmasked After 30 Years |date=15 October 2000 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370421/Bible-John-killer-may-be-unmasked-after-30-years.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref> Unlike Patricia Docker, the body of Jemima McDonald was fully clothed,<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> although her underclothing had been torn, and like Patricia, Jemima had been [[menstruation|menstruating]] at the time of her death.<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nPolice inquiries into Jemima's movements on the night of her murder produced several [[Eyewitness memory|eyewitness]]es who were able to accurately describe the man with whom Jemima had been in the company of at the Barrowland. Door-to-door inquiries on MacKieth Street also produced a woman who remembered hearing female screams on the evening of Jemima's murder, although this individual could not recall the precise time. Consequently, police considered this information of little use to their inquiry.\n\n==Initial investigation==\nAlthough the [[City of Glasgow Police]] noted several striking similarities between the murders of Patricia Docker and Jemima McDonald, including that both women had attended the Barrowland Ballroom on the evening of their murder, been beaten before being strangled to death with a ligature, were menstruating, and had their handbags taken from the crime scene. Initially, both murders were not considered to be the work of the same perpetrator.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=194}}\n\nDespite extensive public appeals, the investigation into the murder of Patricia Docker in 1968 had quickly become a [[cold case]]. Police had little information, owing to both a lack of [[witness]]es and hard evidence.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=193}} The investigation had also been severely hindered by  investigators discovering three days after her death that Patricia had attended the Barrowland Ballroom on the evening of her murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/i-think-bible-john-already-11923937|title=False Information Doomed Bible John Probe from the Start|website=The Daily Record|last=Silvester|first=Norman|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DANCING+WITH+DEATH%3B+CHASING+KILLERS%3A+RETIRED+COP+JOE+JACKSON+ON+THE...-a0186026767|title=Dancing With Death: Chasing Killers|publisher=[[The Free Library]]|website=Daily Record|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> Eighteen months later, following the discovery of Jemima McDonald, police became aware of remarkable similarities to the murder of Patricia Docker. Although police did not conclusively link both murders to the same perpetrator, they could not completely discount this theory. In addition, police were certain the perpetrator or perpetrators held a high degree of local geographical knowledge. However, they may have been a stranger to the district, as none of the eyewitnesses with whom investigators conversed directly knew the individual(s) seen in the company of either woman prior to her murder.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\"/>\n[[File:Barrowlands, Glasgow - geograph.org.uk - 663608.jpg|thumb|right|The Barrowland Ballroom, seen here in 2011. Each of the women murdered are believed to have encountered Bible John at this dance hall]]\n\nFor the first time in a Scottish murder hunt, a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of the man with whom Jemima had last been seen alive was given to the press, being widely distributed via both newspapers and upon television throughout Scotland in efforts to identify the suspect.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> Moreover, both male and female [[Undercover operation|undercover police officers]] performed discreet surveillance at the Barrowland Ballroom in efforts to identify the suspect.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=196}} Police surveillance at the Barrowland Ballroom would be terminated in late October 1969 due to the initiative both failing to produce any suspects. Detectives were also blamed by proprietors for a sharp decrease in attendance figures.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=196-197}}\n\n===Helen Puttock===\nOn 31 October 1969, a man walking his dog discovered the body of 29-year-old Helen Puttock behind a [[tenement]] in the [[Scotstoun]] district of Glasgow. Her body was found beside a drainpipe in the back garden of her Earl Street flat. She had been stripped partially naked, extensively beaten about the face before being raped, then strangled to death with one of her own stockings.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=201}} The contents of her handbag had been scattered close to her body, although the handbag itself was missing from the crime scene. Grass and weed stains upon the soles of Helen's feet and shoes indicated that she had engaged in a ferocious struggle with her killer. She had evidently at one point attempted to scale a nearby railway embankment. Her body also bore a deep [[forensic dentistry|bite mark]] on her upper right thigh.<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/> Her murderer had placed her [[sanitary towel]] beneath her left arm. As had been the case with the two previous victims, Helen had been menstruating at the time of her murder.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=17}}\n\nThe evening prior to her murder, Helen and her sister, Jean Langford, had been to the Barrowland Ballroom, where both had become acquainted with men named John. One of these individuals had said he worked as a [[slater]] who resided in [[Castlemilk]],{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} while the other individual had been a well-spoken man who did not disclose where he actually lived. After being in the company of these two individuals for in excess of an hour, all four left the Barrowland to head home. The individual named John who had been Jean's dance partner walked to [[George Square]] to board a bus, while Jean, Helen, and the individual who had been Helen's dance partner hailed a taxi.<ref name=\"Hamilton\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/legendary-glasgow-detective-tells-believes-1052300|title=Legendary Glasgow detective tells why he believes serial killer Peter Tobin was notorious murderer Bible John|work=Daily Record|last=Hamilton|first=Tom|date=5 March 2010|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The trio set off from [[Glasgow Cross]], making a 20-minute westward journey toward Jean's [[Knightswood]] residence. There she exited the taxi, which then continued towards Helen's Scotstoun residence. During conversations between the trio upon this journey, most of the crucial information pertaining to the killer's [[psychological profiling|psychological profile]] became apparent.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/>\n\nJean later informed detectives{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}} that her sister's companion had been a [[teetotalism|teetotal]] individual{{sfn|Newton|2004|p=42}} who repeatedly quoted from the [[Old Testament]] stories of [[Moses]] during the time she and her sister had conversed with him in the taxi; having previously referred to the Barrowland as an \"[[adultery|adulterous]] den of [[wikt:iniquity|iniquity]]\", and of his disapproval of married women visiting the premises as the quartet had retrieved their coats at the end of the evening.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Detective Still Convinced Bible John is Behind Bars |date=23 February 2018 |url=https://stv.tv/news/features/1408962-former-detective-still-convinced-bible-john-is-behind-bars/ |work=STV News |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> She had herself alighted the taxi at Kelso Street, before viewing the taxi turn towards Earl Street.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\">''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 36. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> {{refn|group=n|Helen Puttock had been married at the time of her murder, although she did not disclose this fact to her murderer.}}{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}}\n\n==Suspect==\nThe suspect was described by Helen's sister Jean as being a tall, slim and well-dressed young man with reddish or fair hair rounded neatly at the back,{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=199}} aged between 25 and 30, and approximately {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m}} in height. This individual had given his name as either \"John Templeton\", \"John Sempleson\", or \"John Emerson\", and he had been a polite and well-spoken individual,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mountflorida.eveningtimes.co.uk/area/dark-days-and-dreadful-deeds-that-haunt-our-city.html|title=Dark days and dreadful deeds that haunt our city|work=Evening Times|date=7 June 2005|accessdate=26 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208143050/http://mountflorida.eveningtimes.co.uk/area/dark-days-and-dreadful-deeds-that-haunt-our-city.html|archivedate=8 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> having frequently quoted from the Old Testament during the trio's taxi ride home,<ref name=Findlay/> although he had indicated he was neither a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] nor [[Protestantism|Protestant]] individual.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\"/> Jean would also state to investigators it had become increasingly clear to her as the trio had ridden in the taxi that this individual had considered her presence in the vehicle to be an inconvenience.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=200}} At one point during this ride, this individual had explained to the women the reason he refrained from consuming alcohol was due to his being conditioned so by a strict parental attitude, before adding: \"I don't drink at [[Hogmanay]]; I pray.\" He had also alluded to his father's belief that dance halls were \"dens of iniquity\", with any married woman who frequented these premises being \"adulterous\" by nature.<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/>{{refn|group=n|The suspect's repeatedly referencing quotes from the Old Testament led to ''[[Evening Times]]'' journalist John Quinn naming the unknown murderer \"Bible John\".{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}}}}\n\nAlthough Jean Langford had informed detectives that the man accompanying Helen had been a \"slim, tall\" individual who had been dressed in a well-cut brown ''Reid and Taylor'' brand suit{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=54}} who smoked ''[[Embassy (cigarette)|Embassy]]'' cigarettes,<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\"/> she also recalled this individual mentioning that he had been familiar with several drinking premises in the [[Yoker]] district of Glasgow,{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} and that he had at one stage worked in a laboratory.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}} She would also recall distinct facial features of this man, such as his having overlapping front teeth. (Bouncers at the Barrowland Ballroom dismissed much of this description, claiming that the man in Helen's company had been a short and well-spoken individual with black hair.)<ref name=\"DR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/crime-professor-quizzes-detective-centre-1077102|title=Crime professor quizzes detective at centre of search for Bible John|work=Daily Record|date=28 November 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Police initially considered the description provided by the bouncers to be a more reliable description than that provided by Jean Langford, as she had allegedly been [[alcohol intoxication|intoxicated]] at the time she and her sister had left. Furthermore, police had reason to believe that the killer had not been quoting directly from the Bible, but had simply been referring to it. However, Jean strongly attested to her having been [[sobriety|sober]] at the time she had left the Barrowland, and a bouncer at these premises would later state that staff who worked at the premises were not \"good with faces\".}}\n\nThe last possible sighting of the suspect was made by both the driver and [[Bus conductor|conductor]] upon a night service bus, who noticed a young man matching Jean's description alighting a bus at the junction of Dumbarton Road and Gray Street at approximately 2:00&nbsp;a.m. on 31 October.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} He was in a notably disheveled state, with mud stains on his jacket and a livid red mark on his cheek just beneath one eye. Both witnesses also recalled his repeatedly tucking a short cuff of one sleeve into his jacket sleeve (a man's cuff link had been found alongside the body of Helen Puttock).<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 37. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> This individual was last seen walking towards the public ferry to cross the [[River Clyde]] to the south side of the city.<ref name=\"Wier\"/>\n\n===Link to series===\nThe murder of Helen Puttock held remarkable similarities to the two previous murders, further raising suspicions that all three murders had been committed by the same individual. All of the victims had been mothers of at least one child and had met her murderer at the Barrowland Ballroom. The handbag of each woman was missing. Each victim had been strangled to death; and at least two of these women had been raped prior to her murder.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=21}} In addition, the three women had been escorted home by her killer and murdered within yards of their doorstep, and all had been menstruating at the time of her death.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/> Each had had her sanitary towel or [[tampon]] placed upon, beneath, or near her body,<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/>{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=202-203}} leading to speculation the women had been murdered due to their refusing to engage in intercourse with their murderer due to their periods.<ref>{{cite news|title=Was Peter Tobin Bible John? |date=6 December 2008 |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/was-peter-tobin-bible-john-1-1302021 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"It is quite incredible that this man has eluded us. I am positive this man comes from Glasgow or nearby. He is between 25 and 30, between {{nowrap|5 ft 10 in}} and {{nowrap|6 ft}} tall, has light red hair, good features, blue-grey eyes and a smart modern appearance. I do not think he is a very religious man, but just has a normal intelligent working knowledge of the Bible which he likes to air ... there must be many people who know someone who looks like this artist's impression.\"\n| source = Detective Superintendent Joe Beattie, describing the prime suspect in the Bible John murders (1972).<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n| width = 35em\n}}\n\n==Ongoing investigation==\nWithin hours of the discovery of the body of Helen Puttock, an additional composite drawing of the suspect was created using the detailed description provided by her sister;{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=203}} this composite drawing would rapidly become one of the most famous facial composites in Scotland.<ref name=\"express\">{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/356076/I-am-sure-the-famous-portrait-of-Bible-John-shows-the-wrong-man|title=I am sure the famous portrait of Bible John shows the wrong man|work=[[Daily Express]]|last=Borland|first=Ben|date=4 November 2012|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|At the headquarters of the [[City of Glasgow Police]], Jean Langford happened to view an earlier [[facial composite|composite drawing]] created relating to the chief suspect in the murder of Jemima McDonald. Upon viewing this Identikit, Langford exclaimed, \"That man looks just like him!\"{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=203}}}} Detective Superintendent Joe Beattie asked the public to closely study this composite drawing, should it resemble anyone they knew. Due to the suspect's hair being unfashionably short for the era, over 450 hairdressers in and around Glasgow were shown the updated composite drawing of the suspect, and all dentists in and around Glasgow were asked to examine their records to determine whether they held records of a male patient with overlapping [[incisor]]s and a missing tooth in the upper right jaw. Both lines of inquiry would prove fruitless.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=54}}\n\nMore than 100 detectives were assigned to work full-time on the case, and 50,000 [[witness statement]]s would be taken in subsequent door-to-door inquiries.<ref name=\"Skelton2\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=OhQ-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=HEoMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6523,4393868&dq|title=Bible John: Final Part of a Harrowing Tale of Terror|work=Evening Times|last=Skelton|first=Douglas|date=18 February 1989|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The True Story of Bible John and the Barrowland Killings |date=22 February 2018 |url=https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/history/bible-john-killing-glasgow-barrowlands-11533797 |work=Glasgow Live |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> Ultimately, more than 5,000 potential suspects would be quizzed in relation to the murders in the first year of the inquiry alone, and Jean Langford would be required to attend over 300 [[police lineup|identity parades]],{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}} although she was adamant none of the individuals required to participate in these identity parades had been the individual with whom she had last seen her sister, and all would be cleared of any involvement.<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/> Fearing that the perpetrator would strike again, a team of 16 detectives were instructed to mingle with dancers at all dance halls in Glasgow. In particular, these detectives frequented the Barrowland on Thursday and Saturday nights at the over-25s events, where each victim was presumed to have met her murderer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Two of the three victims murdered by Bible John had been killed on a Thursday, and one on a Saturday.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=190}}}}\n\nDespite the extensive manhunt, no further developments would arise and the investigation into the three murders gradually became cold, with many individuals assigned to the case opining that the perpetrator had either died, been jailed for an unrelated offense, had been incarcerated at a mental hospital, or that senior police officers had known his actual identity, but had been unable to prove he had committed the murders.<ref name=\"MacDougall\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Fwc-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=m0kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4523,2561436&dq|title=Dark world of a dance hall killer|newspaper=Evening Times|last=MacDougall|first=Carl|date=9 October 1987|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Others speculated that he may have simply moved away from the Glasgow district, or murdered whenever in the vicinity;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/bible-john-may-be-in-england-1.213923|title=Bible John may be in England|work=[[The Herald (Scotland)|The Herald]]|date=16 October 2000|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> this possibility prompted police to circulate multiple copies of the composite drawing at all [[British Army]], [[Royal Navy|Navy]] and [[Royal Air Force|Air Force]] bases in the United Kingdom, Europe, and the [[Middle East|Middle]] and [[Far East]], although this potential line of inquiry also failed to produce any significant leads.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Potential suspects==\n===\"John White\"===\nOne former Detective Chief Inspector, Les Brown (then working with the [[Strathclyde Police]]), has supplied current investigators with details of the arrest of a suspect conducted in 1969 which he believes was of an extremely likely perpetrator, but which was dismissed simply because this individual did not have notably overlapping front teeth.\n\nAccording to Les Brown, the man's arguing with a young woman in the Barrowland Ballroom immediately prior to his arrest had greatly raised investigators' concerns, yet\u2014despite the fact the suspect had closely resembled the facial composite and had subsequently supplied police with a false name and address before revealing his true name and address in [[Gorbals|the Gorbals]]\u2014was simply released. According to Brown, the simple fact of this particular suspect not having notably overlapping front teeth - despite one police sergeant's acknowledgement of his being the best suspect yet - was sufficient enough for ordering his release.<ref name=\"Bible John Police Get New Informati\">{{cite news|title=Bible John Police Get New Information on Serial Killer's Identity |date=23 October 2005 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12472387.Bible_John_police_get_new_information_on_serial_killer_apos_s_identity/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral years later, Brown extensively conversed with a detective who had taken the same individual to a hospital after arresting him outside the Barrowland Ballroom at the time of the murders. Although the suspect had needed several stitches in his head following an altercation, as soon as his handcuffs had been released, he escaped from the hospital. At the time of this incident, this individual had also falsely given his name to medical personnel as John White.\n\nIn addition to this basic circumstantial evidence, the \"whole demeanour\" of this individual had led Les Brown and several of his colleagues to believe this individual may have been the perpetrator.<ref name=\"Bible John Police Get New Informati\"/>\n\n===John Irvine McInnes===\nIn 1996, Strathclyde Police [[Burial#Exhumation|exhumed]] the body of John Irvine McInnes from a graveyard in [[Stonehouse, South Lanarkshire]]. McInnes, who had served in the [[Scots Guards]], had committed [[suicide]] in 1980 at the age of 41, having severed the [[brachial artery]] in his upper arm. He had been the cousin of one of the original suspects in the series of murders.<ref name=\"Bizarre suicide of Bible John\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bizarre+suicide+of+Bible+John.-a061271527|title=Bizarre suicide of Bible John|publisher=The Free Library|website=Daily Record|date=30 January 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> A [[Genetic testing|DNA sample]] was taken from McInnes's body for comparison with [[semen analysis|semen samples]] discovered upon the stockings with which victim Helen Puttock had been strangled.<ref name=\"Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Seria\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12036852.DNA_tests_clear_Bible_John_suspect/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|According to a contemporary [[psychiatrist]]'s report, the unusual method of suicide chosen by McInnes was akin to [[psychopathy]], leading to suggestions McInnes may have opted to take his own life in search of the \"ultimate thrill\".<ref name=\"Bizarre suicide of Bible John\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bizarre+suicide+of+Bible+John.-a061271527|title=Bizarre suicide of Bible John|publisher=The Free Library|website=Daily Record|date=30 January 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> }}\n\nThe results of the testing conducted proved inconclusive, with then-[[Lord Advocate]] [[James Mackay, Baron Mackay of Clashfern|Lord Mackay]] stating [[Burden of proof (law)|insufficient evidence]]<ref name=\"Men give DNA in Bible John case\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4089653.stm|title=Men give DNA in Bible John case|work=[[BBC News]]|date=12 December 2004|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> existed to link McInnes with the murder of Helen Puttock.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dna-tests-clear-bible-john-suspect-1.447304|title=DNA tests clear Bible John suspect|work=The Herald|last=Freeman|first=James|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> [[The Crown]] would officially clear McInnes of any involvement in the Bible John murders in July 1996.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12036852.DNA_tests_clear_Bible_John_suspect/|title=DNA Tests Clear Bible John Suspect|work=Herald Scotland|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Peter Tobin===\nSeveral [[Criminology|criminologists]] and investigators have suggested that convicted serial killer [[Peter Tobin]] may have been Bible John. Tobin was convicted in May 2007 of the 2006 murder of a [[Poles|Polish]] student named Angelika Kluk, who had been raped, beaten, then stabbed to death;<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|title=I'm Ashamed I Had Sex With Girl, Priest Tells Murder Trial |date=4 April 2007 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1547590/Im-ashamed-I-had-sex-with-girl-priest-tells-murder-trial.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> he had relocated from [[Shettleston|Shettleston, Glasgow]]<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\"/> to England in 1969 after marrying his first wife, whom he had met at the Barrowland Ballroom the same year as the murders attributed to Bible John had ended.<ref name=\"Wier\">{{cite book|last=Wier|first=Nigel|year=2012|title=British Serial Killers|publisher=AuthorHouseUK|page=226}}</ref> Tobin would subsequently live in [[Brighton]] for 20 years from 1969,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/jul/12/peter-tobin-serial-killer-brighton-search|title=Peter Tobin's former homes searched in hunt for more victims|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/scotland/article6968389.ece|title=Killer question|work=[[The Times]]|date=27 December 2009}}</ref> although from the late 1980s, he would alternately reside in either Scotland or the South of England.<ref name=\"Wilson2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/books/features/a-life-of-crime-professor-david-wilson-trying-to-understand-why-serial-killers-kill-1-816044|title=A life of crime: Professor David Wilson \u2013 trying to understand why serial killers kill|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=4 July 2010|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|A former detective named Joe Jackson (who had investigated the ''Bible John'' murders in the 1960s) has stated that he suspected Tobin may be the perpetrator shortly after he was arrested for Kluk's murder in 2006, adding: \"When I saw his photograph, I thought, 'This is as near to Bible John as you are going to get. This looks a winner.' He fitted the bill in every way, and he had connections with religion.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/exclusive-cops-believe-peter-tobin-1000204|title=Exclusive: Cops believe Peter Tobin was Bible John|work=Daily Record|last=O'Hare|first=Paul|date=3 December 2008|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nTobin had been in his mid-40s when he committed the 1991 murder of two teenage girls whose [[skeletonization|skeletonized]] bodies would subsequently be unearthed from the garden of his home in [[Margate, Kent]] in 2007. He would be convicted of these murders\u2014alongside that of Kluk\u2014between 2007 and 2009. Commencing serial murderous offences of an extremely calculated nature at such an age is unusual\u2014though not unheard of\u2014for a male. Furthermore, the fact that Tobin had attacked Kluk with such violence, then hidden her body before absconding to London prior to his subsequent arrest in addition to the abduction, restraining and concealment known to have been exhibited upon the two 1991 murder victims unearthed from the garden of his Margate home did not suggest the work of an amateur in any of these three cases.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1823130|title=Expert convinced Tobin is Bible John says more murders likely|work=[[The Press and Journal (Scotland)|The Press and Journal]]|last=Lindsay|first=Morag|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nStriking contemporary visual similarities exist between Peter Tobin when aged in his 20s and the 1969 composite drawing of Bible John. In addition, all three of Tobin's former wives have given accounts of being repeatedly imprisoned, throttled, beaten and raped at his hands, and each has stated he had been driven to extreme physical violence by the female [[menstrual cycle]] (a factor long suspected by investigators as being the perpetrator's actual motive behind the murders).<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/> In addition, Tobin is known to have been a staunch [[Roman Catholic]] with strong religious views,<ref name=Wilson/> and the alias Bible John had given to Jean Langford and Helen Puttock in 1969 is similar to one of the [[pseudonym]]s known to have been regularly used by Tobin: John Semple.<ref name=\"Wilson2\"/>\n\nCriminologist [[David Wilson (criminologist)|David Wilson]] actively investigated Tobin's case for three years and strongly believes the available evidence supports his theory that Peter Tobin is Bible John.<ref name=Wilson/> He has stated that the moment he believed Tobin was Bible John occurred during Tobin's trial for the 1991 murder of 18-year-old Dinah McNicol, one of the women whose body had been unearthed from his Margate garden. The [[circumstantial evidence]] which Wilson uses to support this theory includes striking similarities between trial testimony from an acquaintance of Dinah's who had been in her company on the evening of her abduction and the conversation with Bible John that Jean Langford claimed to have had on the evening of her sister's murder; among the important points of overlap are both men mentioning they did not drink at Hogmanay and had a cousin who had once scored a [[hole-in-one]] in a golf match.<ref name=Wilson/> This information\u2014alongside other circumstantial evidence\u2014has led Professor Wilson to state: \"I didn't set out to prove Tobin was Bible John, but I would stake my professional reputation on it.\"<ref name=Wilson/><ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Genetic testing|DNA testing]] has been used to clear several suspects, detectives believe obtaining a forensic link between Peter Tobin and any of the murder victims linked to Bible John is unlikely due to the deterioration of the physical samples owing to poor storage.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n'''Operation Anagram'''\n\nAs a result of a police investigation named Operation Anagram, which was initiated in 2006 to trace the movements of Tobin throughout the decades and to determine his potential [[culpability]] in any other crimes, a woman informed investigators she had been raped by Tobin after she had met him at the Barrowland Ballroom in 1968, shortly after the first of the murders known to have been committed by Bible John.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10507524|title=Peter Tobin Crimewatch appeal gets 'massive' response|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=6 July 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Another woman informed investigators in 2010 that she had endured a threatening experience with Tobin at the Barrowland Ballroom, claiming that Tobin had introduced himself as Peter, before pestering her to go with him to a party in the city's Castlemilk area. When this woman viewed pictures of Tobin dating from the late 1960s and early 1970s, she stated: \"[He] was the man who came up to me so many years ago in [the] Barrowlands. I am 100 per cent certain [that] Tobin is Bible John.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/bible-john-asked-me-to-dance---1062823|title=Bible John asked me to dance \u2013 it was Peter Tobin, reveals terrified gran|work=Daily Record|last=Stewart|first=Stephen|date=27 June 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nNo further murder victims killed in Scotland or elsewhere in the United Kingdom have ever been conclusively attributed to Bible John,{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=207-208}} and the manhunt for this murderer was one of the most extensive manhunts in Scottish criminal history.<ref name=\"DR\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370421/Bible-John-killer-may-be-unmasked-after-30-years.html|title=Bible John Killer May be Unmasked After 30 Years|work=The Telegraph|last=Booth|first=Jenny|date=15 October 2000|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> The murders of the three women remain unsolved, although the case remains open, with many investigators remaining certain that the perpetrator(s)<ref name=\"Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Seria\"/> of these crimes were highly likely to have been shielded by one or more individuals whom he had known.<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 38. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref>\n\nNo uniform consensus that the three killings were actually the work of the same person exists.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=205}} It has been claimed that the gap of 18 months between the first two killings is unusual for a serial killer, and that the later two murders may have either been copycat killings, or the sole two committed by the same perpetrator. Criticism has also been levelled against the police for potentially hampering their own investigation by prematurely jumping to the conclusion that all three murders had been committed by the same person.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jeffrey|first=Robert|year=2006|title=Crimes Past: Glasgow's Crimes of the Century|publisher=Black and White Publishing}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|[[David Wilson (criminologist)|Professor David Wilson]] has stated that a lapse of time approximating 18 months is not unusual between a serial killer's first and second murders.<ref name=Wilson>{{Cite news|title=Scots murderer Peter Tobin is Bible John, says UK serial killer expert|date=13 June 2010|work=Daily Record|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/scots-murderer-peter-tobin-is-bible-1061592|accessdate=4 March 2019|last=McPherson|first=Lynn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930208&slug=1684320 |title=Serial Killer Says He'd Do It Again |last=Oak Kim |first=Myung |date=8 February 1993 |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |access-date=25 January 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125214432/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930208&slug=1684320 |archivedate=25 January 2017 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1983, an anonymous individual contacted [[Strathclyde Police]]. This individual claimed to conclusively know that his friend had been Bible John. According to this anonymous individual, both he and his friend had been raised in the [[Cranhill]] district of Glasgow, and both had frequented the Barrowland Ballroom in the 1960s. Allegedly, this individual had read an article in the ''[[Evening Times]]'' five years previously before suddenly realising his friend had been the perpetrator of the murders. The alleged suspect was traced living in [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]], married to a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] woman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YNdAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nqYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4240,1151385&dq|title=I know it is him|work=Evening Times|last=Hildrey|first=Mike|date=7 February 1983|accessdate=23 May 2013}}</ref> Nothing more was ever heard from the anonymous individual or the reputed suspect.\n\nIn 2004, police announced their intentions to [[genetic testing|genetically test]] a number of men in a further attempt to identify the perpetrator, with all individuals concerned being requested to submit [[Sampling (medicine)#Body fluid sampling|blood samples]].<ref name=\"Men give DNA in Bible John case\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dna-tests-clear-bible-john-suspect-1.447304|title=DNA tests clear Bible John suspect|work=The Herald|last=Freeman|first=James|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> This endeavour followed the previous discovery of an 80% genetic match from the semen samples retrieved from the final crime scene attributed to Bible John with a DNA sample retrieved at the site of a minor crime committed two years earlier. The sample was enough of a match to lead officers to believe that the person who committed the offence was related to the killer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DNA+BREAKTHROUGH%3A+POLICE+TRACE+FAMILY+OF+BIBLE+JOHN+SERIAL+KILLER.-a0126288448|title=DNA breakthrough: police trace family of Bible John serial killer|publisher=The Free Library|website=Sunday Mail|last=Lavery|first=Charles|date=19 December 2004|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe sole witness ever to have engaged in a lengthy conversation with Bible John, Jean Langford, died in September 2010 at the age of 74.<ref name=Findlay>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/2010/09/26/hunt-for-bible-john-comes-to-an-end-after-only-witness-in-case-dies-86908-22588146/|title=Hunt for Bible John comes to an end after only witness in case dies|date=26 September 2010|accessdate=4 March 2019|work=Daily Record|last=Findlay|first=Russell}}</ref> Langford had given police the description used to form the second composite drawing created of the suspect, which continues to remain the most significant clue as to the perpetrator's physical appearance. Despite Professor Wilson's assertion that Peter Tobin may have been Bible John, when Jean Langford discussed her sister's murderer many decades later, she dismissed this theory, stating emphatically that Tobin had not been the man with whom she had shared a taxi on the night of her sister's murder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whelan|first1=Michael|title=Bible John - Unresolved|url=https://unresolved.me/bible-john/|website=unresolved.me|accessdate=11 July 2018|date=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE SOUTH PARK OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n=== Books ===\n* {{Cite book|last= Harrison|first= Paul|title= Dancing with the Devil: The Bible John Murders|year= 2013|publisher= Vertical Editions|location= Skipton|isbn= 978-1-904-09173-8}}.\n* {{Cite book|last=Malloy|first=Andrew D.|title=Bible John - Closure|year= 2011|publisher= Pneuma Springs Publishing|location= Kent|isbn= 978-1-907-72816-7}}.\n* {{cite book| last = Stoddart| first = Charles| title = Bible John: Search for a Sadist|year = 1980| publisher = Paul Harris Publishing | location = Edinburgh| isbn = 978-0-904-50589-4}}.\n* {{cite book| last1 = Wilson| first1 = David| last2 = Harrison| first2 = Paul| title = The Lost British Serial Killer| year = 2010| publisher = Brown Book Group Limited | location = London| isbn = 978-0-751-54232-5}}\n\n=== Television ===\n* The [[BBC]] has broadcast a 30-minute documentary focusing upon the murders committed by Bible John. Presented by Hugh Cochrane, this episode was screened on 18 September 1970, and concluded with a direct quote from [[Jeremiah]], Chapter 23, Verse 24, appealing to the perpetrator to hand himself in to the police: 'Can any hide himself in secret places, that I shall not see him? saith the Lord?{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}}\n* [[STV (TV channel)|STV]] have broadcast a 45-minute documentary focusing upon the murders committed by Bible John. This documentary, titled ''In Search of Bible John'', was initially broadcast in 2011, and explores the possibility Peter Tobin may have been the perpetrator of the three murders.\n* The case of Bible John featured in a December 2005 episode of ''[[Unsolved (UK TV programme)|Unsolved]].'' Narrated by [[Alex Norton]], the program primarily focuses on the death of the final victim, Helen Puttock, and includes interviews with Puttock's husband.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taggart actor steps in to try to solve Bible John murder riddle |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/taggart-actor-steps-in-to-try-to-solve-bible-john-murder-riddle-1-1096054/amp |accessdate=27 January 2019 |work=The Scotsman |date=17 September 2005}}</ref>\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE THE SIMPSONS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Capital punishment in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of serial killers by number of victims|List of murderers by number of victims]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[List of serial killers by country]]\n* [[Unsolved murders in the United Kingdom]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|1960s|Law|Scotland|United Kingdom}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{Cite book|last= Cawthorne|first= Nigel|title=The Mammoth Book of Killers at Large|year= 2007|publisher=Constable & Robinson Ltd|location= London|isbn= 978-1-845-29631-5}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Harrison|first= Paul|title=Dancing with the Devil: The Bible John Murders|year= 2013|publisher= Vertical Editions|location= Skipton|isbn= 978-1-904-09173-8}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Lane|first= Brian|last2= Gregg|first2= Wilfred|title= The Encyclopedia Of Serial Killers|origyear= 1992|year= 1995|publisher= Berkley Books|location= New York City|isbn= 0-425-15213-8|ref= harv|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofse00lane}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Lloyd|first= Georgina|title= One Was Not Enough: True Stories of Multiple Murderers|year= 1986|publisher= Bantam Books|location= London|isbn= 978-0-553-17605-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Malloy|first=Andrew D.|title=Bible John - Closure|year= 2011|publisher= Pneuma Springs Publishing|location= Kent|isbn= 978-1-907-72816-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Newton| first = Michael| title = The Encyclopedia of Unsolved Crimes|year = 2004| publisher = Facts on File | location = New York| isbn = 978-0-816-07818-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Stoddart| first = Charles| title = Bible John: Search for a Sadist|year = 1980| publisher = Paul Harris Publishing | location = Edinburgh| isbn = 978-0-904-50589-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Whittington-Egan| first = Molly| title = Scottish Murder Stories|year = 1998| publisher = Neil Wilson Publishing Ltd.| location = Glasgow| isbn = 978-1-906-47647-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Whittington-Egan|first= Richard|last2= Whittington-Egan|first2= Molly|title= The Murder Almanac|year= 1992|publisher= Neil Wilson Publishing Ltd.|location= Glasgow|isbn= 978-1-897-78404-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last1 = Wilson| first1 = Colin| last2 = Wilson| first2 = Damon| last3 = Wilson| first3 = Rowan| title = World Famous Murders| year = 1993| publisher = Parragon Publishing| location = London| isbn = 978-0-752-50122-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* 2000 ''[[BBC News]]'' account detailing [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/971771.stm contemporary developments] pertaining to leads in the Bible John inquiry\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051104053053/http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/unsolved/bible_john/index.html Bible John] at Court TV's ''Crime Library''\n* [https://www.historicmysteries.com/bible-john/ Bible John] at ''historicmysteries.com''\n* [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=GGgVawPscysC&dat=19691101&printsec=frontpage&hl=en Contemporary edition] of ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Glasgow Herald]]'', focusing upon the discovery of the body of Helen Puttock (p.&nbsp;1)\n* [https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/history/bible-john-killing-glasgow-barrowlands-11533797 ''glasgowlive.co.uk''] article pertaining to Bible John\n* International Crime Writing Festival [https://bloodyscotland.com/events/who-was-bible-john/ article focusing upon the Bible John murders]\n* [https://www.trace-evidence.com/008/ ''The Bible John Murders''] at trace-evidence.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John, Bible}}\n[[Category:1968 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1969 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1960s in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:1968 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1969 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish criminals]]\n[[Category:History of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Murder in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Murder in Scotland]]\n[[Category:People associated with Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish rapists]]\n[[Category:Scottish serial killers]]\n[[Category:Scottish sex offenders]]\n[[Category:Unidentified serial killers]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name=Bible John\n| image     = File:Bible_John_1969_Police_Composite_Sketch.jpg\n| caption   = 1969 [[Facial composite|composite drawing]] of ''Bible John''\n| alt       = Composite drawing of Bible John, created with the assistance of the sister of his last known victim, Helen Puttock\n| victims= 3 \n| locations = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]\n| beginyear= 22 February 1968\n| endyear= 31 October 1969\n| apprehended= Unapprehended \n}}\n\n'''Bible John''' is an unidentified [[serial killer]] who is believed to have murdered three young women between 1968 and 1969 in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lister|first=David Brown, Sean O\u2019Neill and David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bible-john-the-sanctimonious-dancehall-killer-who-vanished-gmfgpwb7j6d|title=\u2018Bible John\u2019 \u2013 the sanctimonious dancehall killer who vanished|access-date=2020-03-07|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nEach of the victims of Bible John were young [[brunette]] women between the ages of 25 and 32, and all had met their murderer at the [[Barrowland Ballroom]]: a [[dance hall]] and [[music venue]] in the city. The perpetrator has never been identified and the case remains both unsolved and also one of the most extensive [[manhunt (law enforcement)|manhunts]] in Scottish criminal history.<ref>{{cite book|title=Glasgow Almanac: An A-Z of the City and its People|isbn=978-1-906-47625-0|page=112|location=Glasgow|publisher=Neil Wilson Publishing|year=2011|first=Stephen|last=Terry}}</ref>\n\nThe murders committed by Bible John would prove to be the first time in Scotland in which the [[Clerk of the Crown in Chancery|Crown Office]] authorised the publication of a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of an individual suspected of murder for public viewing.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=18}}\n\nThis unidentified serial killer became known as \"Bible John\" due to his having repeatedly quoted from the [[Christian Bible|Bible]] and to have condemned any form of [[adultery]] while in the company of his final victim.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=21}} The known movements and ''[[modus operandi]]'' of convicted serial killer and rapist [[Peter Tobin]] have given rise to suspicions that he may be Bible John.\n\n==First murders==\n===Patricia Docker===\nOn 23 February 1968, the naked body of a 25-year-old [[auxiliary nurse]] named Patricia Docker was found in the doorway of a lock-up garage by a man on his way to work in [[Battlefield, Glasgow|Battlefield, South Glasgow]].<ref name=\"Skelton\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=v-NAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3KYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1709,2603592&dq|title=20 years on, the mystery of Bible John still haunts a city|newspaper=[[Evening Times]]|last=Skelton|first=Douglas|date=10 February 1989|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The location of her body was only yards from her home in Langside Place. Her body bore evidence of extensive [[blunt force trauma]]\u2014particularly to the face and head.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=17}} She had been [[strangulation|strangled]] to death with a strong [[strangling#Ligature strangulation|ligature]], possibly a belt.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=52}} Patricia's handbag, watch, and clothes were missing from the [[crime scene]]. Her clothing was never found,<ref name=\"MacDougall\"/> although her handbag was later recovered from the [[River Cart]] by an [[underwater search and recovery|underwater search unit]],{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}} whereas her watch was recovered from a pool of water close to the scene of her murder.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\">''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 34. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref>\n\nExtensive door-to-door inquiries in the area produced a witness who recalled hearing a female scream, \"Leave me alone!\" the previous evening. Little [[smoking gun|hard evidence]] was discovered at the crime scene. Nonetheless, an ambulanceman who retrieved the body informed investigators the victim had been a nurse who worked at Mearnskirk Hospital in nearby [[Renfrewshire]].<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> Consequently, the victim was formally identified by her father the following day.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=191}}\n\nPatricia was a married mother of one but [[family estrangement|estranged]] from her husband.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> The night of her murder, she informed her parents she would spend the evening dancing at the Majestic Ballroom in nearby Hope Street, although for unknown reasons, she had chosen to spend the majority of the evening at the Barrowland Ballroom, likely to attend the over-25s night which the Barrowland hosted each Thursday.<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> When she failed to return home that evening, her parents assumed she had spent the night with a friend.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petrie|first1=Ewan|title=Bible John: Remembering Notorious Serial Killer's Victims|url=https://stv.tv/news/features/1408716-bible-john-victims-of-notorious-glasgow-serial-killer/|publisher=STV|accessdate=23 July 2018|date=23 February 2018}}</ref> Police inquiries would only determine several days later<ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> that in the late evening, Patricia had left the Majestic Ballroom to attend the Barrowland,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DANCING+WITH+DEATH%3B+CHASING+KILLERS%3A+RETIRED+COP+JOE+JACKSON+ON+THE...-a0186026767|title=Dancing With Death; Chasing Killers|publisher=[[The Free Library]]|website=Daily Record|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> where she had likely encountered her killer.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/><ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[autopsy|postmortem]] conducted by Gilbert Forbes at the [[University of Glasgow Medical School]] confirmed that the cause of death had been strangulation, and that Patricia's body bore no clear evidence of [[sexual assault]].{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=192}}<ref name=\"heraldscotland.com\"/> Furthermore, the stage of [[rigor mortis]] upon her body at the time of discovery indicated she had likely died shortly after she had left the Barrowland Ballroom.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=52}} Investigators surmised the perpetrator had likely grabbed Patricia before repeatedly punching her and kicking her in the face as she twice screamed \"Leave me alone!\"<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/> He had then proceeded to [[rape]] Patricia before strangling her to death, and leaving her naked body, with nothing but one shoe nearby, close to the doorway of the lock-up garage at Carmichael Place.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/>\n\n===Jemima McDonald===\nOn Saturday, 16 August 1969, a 32-year-old mother of three named Jemima McDonald also opted to attend the Barrowland Ballroom to spend the evening dancing. Jemima was a regular attendee of the Barrowland, and as per family custom, her sister, Margaret O'Brien, took care of her three children as Jemima attended the Barrowland.<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 35. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> As midnight approached, Jemima was seen by several people in the company of a young, well-dressed and well-spoken man of slim build aged between 25 and 35 and between {{nowrap|6 ft 0 in}} and {{nowrap|6 ft 2 in}} ({{convert|72|and|74|in|cm|disp=out}}) in height.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=195}} This individual had short, dark brown hair with fair streaks,{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=253}} likely spoke with a distinctive [[Glasgow accent|Glaswegian accent]], and occasionally inserted brief Biblical quotations into his conversation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nJemima was seen leaving the Barrowland shortly after midnight on 17 August in the company of this individual, and was last seen walking towards either Main Street or Landressy Street, in the direction of her home, at approximately 12:40&nbsp;a.m.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=195}} The following day, Jemima's sister, Margaret, became concerned when her sister failed to return home. Later the same day, she began hearing local rumours that young children had been seen leaving a derelict [[tenement]] building in MacKeith Street discussing a body in the premises.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> By the Monday morning, Margaret was so concerned that she herself, fearing the worst, walked into the old building. There she discovered her own sister's extensively battered body lying face down, with her shoes and stockings lying beside her.\n\nA postmortem concluded Jemima had been raped and extensively beaten, particularly about the face,<ref name=\"Bible John p. 34\"/> before she had been strangled to death with one of her own stockings. Her murder had occurred approximately 30 hours before her body had been discovered.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Bible John Killer may be Unmasked After 30 Years |date=15 October 2000 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370421/Bible-John-killer-may-be-unmasked-after-30-years.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=19 June 2018}}</ref> Unlike Patricia Docker, the body of Jemima McDonald was fully clothed,<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> although her underclothing had been torn, and like Patricia, Jemima had been [[menstruation|menstruating]] at the time of her death.<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nPolice inquiries into Jemima's movements on the night of her murder produced several [[Eyewitness memory|eyewitness]]es who were able to accurately describe the man with whom Jemima had been in the company of at the Barrowland. Door-to-door inquiries on MacKieth Street also produced a woman who remembered hearing female screams on the evening of Jemima's murder, although this individual could not recall the precise time. Consequently, police considered this information of little use to their inquiry.\n\n==Initial investigation==\nAlthough the [[City of Glasgow Police]] noted several striking similarities between the murders of Patricia Docker and Jemima McDonald, including that both women had attended the Barrowland Ballroom on the evening of their murder, been beaten before being strangled to death with a ligature, were menstruating, and had their handbags taken from the crime scene. Initially, both murders were not considered to be the work of the same perpetrator.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=194}}\n\nDespite extensive public appeals, the investigation into the murder of Patricia Docker in 1968 had quickly become a [[cold case]]. Police had little information, owing to both a lack of [[witness]]es and hard evidence.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=193}} The investigation had also been severely hindered by  investigators discovering three days after her death that Patricia had attended the Barrowland Ballroom on the evening of her murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/i-think-bible-john-already-11923937|title=False Information Doomed Bible John Probe from the Start|website=The Daily Record|last=Silvester|first=Norman|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DANCING+WITH+DEATH%3B+CHASING+KILLERS%3A+RETIRED+COP+JOE+JACKSON+ON+THE...-a0186026767|title=Dancing With Death: Chasing Killers|publisher=[[The Free Library]]|website=Daily Record|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> Eighteen months later, following the discovery of Jemima McDonald, police became aware of remarkable similarities to the murder of Patricia Docker. Although police did not conclusively link both murders to the same perpetrator, they could not completely discount this theory. In addition, police were certain the perpetrator or perpetrators held a high degree of local geographical knowledge. However, they may have been a stranger to the district, as none of the eyewitnesses with whom investigators conversed directly knew the individual(s) seen in the company of either woman prior to her murder.<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\"/>\n[[File:Barrowlands, Glasgow - geograph.org.uk - 663608.jpg|thumb|right|The Barrowland Ballroom, seen here in 2011. Each of the women murdered are believed to have encountered Bible John at this dance hall]]\n\nFor the first time in a Scottish murder hunt, a [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of the man with whom Jemima had last been seen alive was given to the press, being widely distributed via both newspapers and upon television throughout Scotland in efforts to identify the suspect.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/> Moreover, both male and female [[Undercover operation|undercover police officers]] performed discreet surveillance at the Barrowland Ballroom in efforts to identify the suspect.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=196}} Police surveillance at the Barrowland Ballroom would be terminated in late October 1969 due to the initiative both failing to produce any suspects. Detectives were also blamed by proprietors for a sharp decrease in attendance figures.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=196-197}}\n\n===Helen Puttock===\nOn 31 October 1969, a man walking his dog discovered the body of 29-year-old Helen Puttock behind a [[tenement]] in the [[Scotstoun]] district of Glasgow. Her body was found beside a drainpipe in the back garden of her Earl Street flat. She had been stripped partially naked, extensively beaten about the face before being raped, then strangled to death with one of her own stockings.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=201}} The contents of her handbag had been scattered close to her body, although the handbag itself was missing from the crime scene. Grass and weed stains upon the soles of Helen's feet and shoes indicated that she had engaged in a ferocious struggle with her killer. She had evidently at one point attempted to scale a nearby railway embankment. Her body also bore a deep [[forensic dentistry|bite mark]] on her upper right thigh.<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/> Her murderer had placed her [[sanitary towel]] beneath her left arm. As had been the case with the two previous victims, Helen had been menstruating at the time of her murder.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|Whittington-Egan|1992|p=17}}\n\nThe evening prior to her murder, Helen and her sister, Jean Langford, had been to the Barrowland Ballroom, where both had become acquainted with men named John. One of these individuals had said he worked as a [[slater]] who resided in [[Castlemilk]],{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} while the other individual had been a well-spoken man who did not disclose where he actually lived. After being in the company of these two individuals for in excess of an hour, all four left the Barrowland to head home. The individual named John who had been Jean's dance partner walked to [[George Square]] to board a bus, while Jean, Helen, and the individual who had been Helen's dance partner hailed a taxi.<ref name=\"Hamilton\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/legendary-glasgow-detective-tells-believes-1052300|title=Legendary Glasgow detective tells why he believes serial killer Peter Tobin was notorious murderer Bible John|work=Daily Record|last=Hamilton|first=Tom|date=5 March 2010|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The trio set off from [[Glasgow Cross]], making a 20-minute westward journey toward Jean's [[Knightswood]] residence. There she exited the taxi, which then continued towards Helen's Scotstoun residence. During conversations between the trio upon this journey, most of the crucial information pertaining to the killer's [[psychological profiling|psychological profile]] became apparent.<ref name=\"Skelton\"/>\n\nJean later informed detectives{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}} that her sister's companion had been a [[teetotalism|teetotal]] individual{{sfn|Newton|2004|p=42}} who repeatedly quoted from the [[Old Testament]] stories of [[Moses]] during the time she and her sister had conversed with him in the taxi; having previously referred to the Barrowland as an \"[[adultery|adulterous]] den of [[wikt:iniquity|iniquity]]\", and of his disapproval of married women visiting the premises as the quartet had retrieved their coats at the end of the evening.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Detective Still Convinced Bible John is Behind Bars |date=23 February 2018 |url=https://stv.tv/news/features/1408962-former-detective-still-convinced-bible-john-is-behind-bars/ |work=STV News |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref> She had herself alighted the taxi at Kelso Street, before viewing the taxi turn towards Earl Street.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\">''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 36. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> {{refn|group=n|Helen Puttock had been married at the time of her murder, although she did not disclose this fact to her murderer.}}{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=53}}\n\n==Suspect==\nThe suspect was described by Helen's sister Jean as being a tall, slim and well-dressed young man with reddish or fair hair rounded neatly at the back,{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=199}} aged between 25 and 30, and approximately {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m}} in height. This individual had given his name as either \"John Templeton\", \"John Sempleson\", or \"John Emerson\", and he had been a polite and well-spoken individual,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mountflorida.eveningtimes.co.uk/area/dark-days-and-dreadful-deeds-that-haunt-our-city.html|title=Dark days and dreadful deeds that haunt our city|work=Evening Times|date=7 June 2005|accessdate=26 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208143050/http://mountflorida.eveningtimes.co.uk/area/dark-days-and-dreadful-deeds-that-haunt-our-city.html|archivedate=8 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> having frequently quoted from the Old Testament during the trio's taxi ride home,<ref name=Findlay/> although he had indicated he was neither a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] nor [[Protestantism|Protestant]] individual.<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\"/> Jean would also state to investigators it had become increasingly clear to her as the trio had ridden in the taxi that this individual had considered her presence in the vehicle to be an inconvenience.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=200}} At one point during this ride, this individual had explained to the women the reason he refrained from consuming alcohol was due to his being conditioned so by a strict parental attitude, before adding: \"I don't drink at [[Hogmanay]]; I pray.\" He had also alluded to his father's belief that dance halls were \"dens of iniquity\", with any married woman who frequented these premises being \"adulterous\" by nature.<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/>{{refn|group=n|The suspect's repeatedly referencing quotes from the Old Testament led to ''[[Evening Times]]'' journalist John Quinn naming the unknown murderer \"Bible John\".{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}}}}\n\nAlthough Jean Langford had informed detectives that the man accompanying Helen had been a \"slim, tall\" individual who had been dressed in a well-cut brown ''Reid and Taylor'' brand suit{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=54}} who smoked ''[[Embassy (cigarette)|Embassy]]'' cigarettes,<ref name=\"Bible John p. 36\"/> she also recalled this individual mentioning that he had been familiar with several drinking premises in the [[Yoker]] district of Glasgow,{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} and that he had at one stage worked in a laboratory.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}} She would also recall distinct facial features of this man, such as his having overlapping front teeth. (Bouncers at the Barrowland Ballroom dismissed much of this description, claiming that the man in Helen's company had been a short and well-spoken individual with black hair.)<ref name=\"DR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/crime-professor-quizzes-detective-centre-1077102|title=Crime professor quizzes detective at centre of search for Bible John|work=Daily Record|date=28 November 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Police initially considered the description provided by the bouncers to be a more reliable description than that provided by Jean Langford, as she had allegedly been [[alcohol intoxication|intoxicated]] at the time she and her sister had left the Barrowland Ballroom on the night of Helen's murder. Furthermore, police had reason to believe that the killer had not been quoting directly from the Bible, but had simply been referring to it. However, Jean strongly attested to her having been [[sobriety|sober]] at the time she had left the Barrowland, and a bouncer at these premises would later state that staff who worked at the premises were not \"good with faces\".}}\n\nThe last possible sighting of the suspect was made by both the driver and [[Bus conductor|conductor]] upon a night service bus, who noticed a young man matching Jean's description alighting a bus at the junction of Dumbarton Road and Gray Street at approximately 2:00&nbsp;a.m. on 31 October.{{sfn|Whittington-Egan|1998|loc=ch. 15}} He was in a notably disheveled state, with mud stains on his jacket and a livid red mark on his cheek just beneath one eye. Both witnesses also recalled his repeatedly tucking a short cuff of one sleeve into his jacket sleeve (a man's cuff link had been found alongside the body of Helen Puttock).<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 37. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref> This individual was last seen walking towards the public ferry to cross the [[River Clyde]] to the south side of the city.<ref name=\"Wier\"/>\n\n===Link to series===\nThe murder of Helen Puttock held remarkable similarities to the two previous murders, further raising suspicions that all three murders had been committed by the same individual. All of the victims had been mothers of at least one child and had met her murderer at the Barrowland Ballroom. The handbag of each woman was missing. Each victim had been strangled to death; and at least two of these women had been raped prior to her murder.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=21}} In addition, the three women had been escorted home by her killer and murdered within yards of their doorstep, and all had been menstruating at the time of her death.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/> Each had had her sanitary towel or [[tampon]] placed upon, beneath, or near her body,<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/>{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=202-203}} leading to speculation the women had been murdered due to their refusing to engage in intercourse with their murderer due to their periods.<ref>{{cite news|title=Was Peter Tobin Bible John? |date=6 December 2008 |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/was-peter-tobin-bible-john-1-1302021 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"It is quite incredible that this man has eluded us. I am positive this man comes from Glasgow or nearby. He is between 25 and 30, between {{nowrap|5 ft 10 in}} and {{nowrap|6 ft}} tall, has light red hair, good features, blue-grey eyes and a smart modern appearance. I do not think he is a very religious man, but just has a normal intelligent working knowledge of the Bible which he likes to air ... there must be many people who know someone who looks like this artist's impression.\"\n| source = Detective Superintendent Joe Beattie, describing the prime suspect in the Bible John murders (1972).<ref name=\"Maule\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n| width = 35em\n}}\n\n==Ongoing investigation==\nWithin hours of the discovery of the body of Helen Puttock, an additional composite drawing of the suspect was created using the detailed description provided by her sister;{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=203}} this composite drawing would rapidly become one of the most famous facial composites in Scotland.<ref name=\"express\">{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/356076/I-am-sure-the-famous-portrait-of-Bible-John-shows-the-wrong-man|title=I am sure the famous portrait of Bible John shows the wrong man|work=[[Daily Express]]|last=Borland|first=Ben|date=4 November 2012|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|At the headquarters of the [[City of Glasgow Police]], Jean Langford happened to view an earlier [[facial composite|composite drawing]] created relating to the chief suspect in the murder of Jemima McDonald. Upon viewing this Identikit, Langford exclaimed, \"That man looks just like him!\"{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=203}}}} Detective Superintendent Joe Beattie asked the public to closely study this composite drawing, should it resemble anyone they knew. Due to the suspect's hair being unfashionably short for the era, over 450 hairdressers in and around Glasgow were shown the updated composite drawing of the suspect, and all dentists in and around Glasgow were asked to examine their records to determine whether they held records of a male patient with overlapping [[incisor]]s and a missing tooth in the upper right jaw. Both lines of inquiry would prove fruitless.{{sfn|Lane|Gregg|1995|p=54}}\n\nMore than 100 detectives were assigned to work full-time on the case, and 50,000 [[witness statement]]s would be taken in subsequent door-to-door inquiries.<ref name=\"Skelton2\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=OhQ-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=HEoMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6523,4393868&dq|title=Bible John: Final Part of a Harrowing Tale of Terror|work=Evening Times|last=Skelton|first=Douglas|date=18 February 1989|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The True Story of Bible John and the Barrowland Killings |date=22 February 2018 |url=https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/history/bible-john-killing-glasgow-barrowlands-11533797 |work=Glasgow Live |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref> Ultimately, more than 5,000 potential suspects would be quizzed in relation to the murders in the first year of the inquiry alone, and Jean Langford would be required to attend over 300 [[police lineup|identity parades]],{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}} although she was adamant none of the individuals required to participate in these identity parades had been the individual with whom she had last seen her sister, and all would be cleared of any involvement.<ref name=\"Skelton2\"/> Fearing that the perpetrator would strike again, a team of 16 detectives were instructed to mingle with dancers at all dance halls in Glasgow. In particular, these detectives frequented the Barrowland on Thursday and Saturday nights at the over-25s events, where each victim was presumed to have met her murderer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|Two of the three victims murdered by Bible John had been killed on a Thursday, and one on a Saturday.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=190}}}}\n\nDespite the extensive manhunt, no further developments would arise and the investigation into the three murders gradually became cold, with many individuals assigned to the case opining that the perpetrator had either died, been jailed for an unrelated offense, had been incarcerated at a mental hospital, or that senior police officers had known his actual identity, but had been unable to prove he had committed the murders.<ref name=\"MacDougall\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Fwc-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=m0kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4523,2561436&dq|title=Dark world of a dance hall killer|newspaper=Evening Times|last=MacDougall|first=Carl|date=9 October 1987|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Others speculated that he may have simply moved away from the Glasgow district, or murdered whenever in the vicinity;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/bible-john-may-be-in-england-1.213923|title=Bible John may be in England|work=[[The Herald (Scotland)|The Herald]]|date=16 October 2000|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> this possibility prompted police to circulate multiple copies of the composite drawing at all [[British Army]], [[Royal Navy|Navy]] and [[Royal Air Force|Air Force]] bases in the United Kingdom, Europe, and the [[Middle East|Middle]] and [[Far East]], although this potential line of inquiry also failed to produce any significant leads.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yQUrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EJgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3386,3743142&dq|title=Bible John, the Dancing Strangler|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|last=Maule|first=Henry|date=27 February 1972|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Potential suspects==\n===\"John White\"===\nOne former Detective Chief Inspector, Les Brown (then working with the [[Strathclyde Police]]), has supplied current investigators with details of the arrest of a suspect conducted in 1969 which he believes was of an extremely likely perpetrator, but which was dismissed simply because this individual did not have notably overlapping front teeth.\n\nAccording to Les Brown, the man's arguing with a young woman in the Barrowland Ballroom immediately prior to his arrest had greatly raised investigators' concerns, yet\u2014despite the fact the suspect had closely resembled the facial composite and had subsequently supplied police with a false name and address before revealing his true name and address in [[Gorbals|the Gorbals]]\u2014was simply released. According to Brown, the simple fact of this particular suspect not having notably overlapping front teeth - despite one police sergeant's acknowledgement of his being the best suspect yet - was sufficient enough for ordering his release.<ref name=\"Bible John Police Get New Informati\">{{cite news|title=Bible John Police Get New Information on Serial Killer's Identity |date=23 October 2005 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12472387.Bible_John_police_get_new_information_on_serial_killer_apos_s_identity/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral years later, Brown extensively conversed with a detective who had taken the same individual to a hospital after arresting him outside the Barrowland Ballroom at the time of the murders. Although the suspect had needed several stitches in his head following an altercation, as soon as his handcuffs had been released, he escaped from the hospital. At the time of this incident, this individual had also falsely given his name to medical personnel as John White.\n\nIn addition to this basic circumstantial evidence, the \"whole demeanour\" of this individual had led Les Brown and several of his colleagues to believe this individual may have been the perpetrator.<ref name=\"Bible John Police Get New Informati\"/>\n\n===John Irvine McInnes===\nIn 1996, Strathclyde Police [[Burial#Exhumation|exhumed]] the body of John Irvine McInnes from a graveyard in [[Stonehouse, South Lanarkshire]]. McInnes, who had served in the [[Scots Guards]], had committed [[suicide]] in 1980 at the age of 41, having severed the [[brachial artery]] in his upper arm. He had been the cousin of one of the original suspects in the series of murders.<ref name=\"Bizarre suicide of Bible John\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bizarre+suicide+of+Bible+John.-a061271527|title=Bizarre suicide of Bible John|publisher=The Free Library|website=Daily Record|date=30 January 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> A [[Genetic testing|DNA sample]] was taken from McInnes's body for comparison with [[semen analysis|semen samples]] discovered upon the stockings with which victim Helen Puttock had been strangled.<ref name=\"Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Seria\">{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12036852.DNA_tests_clear_Bible_John_suspect/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=17 July 2018}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|According to a contemporary [[psychiatrist]]'s report, the unusual method of suicide chosen by McInnes was akin to [[psychopathy]], leading to suggestions McInnes may have opted to take his own life in search of the \"ultimate thrill\".<ref name=\"Bizarre suicide of Bible John\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Bizarre+suicide+of+Bible+John.-a061271527|title=Bizarre suicide of Bible John|publisher=The Free Library|website=Daily Record|date=30 January 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> }}\n\nThe results of the testing conducted proved inconclusive, with then-[[Lord Advocate]] [[James Mackay, Baron Mackay of Clashfern|Lord Mackay]] stating [[Burden of proof (law)|insufficient evidence]]<ref name=\"Men give DNA in Bible John case\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4089653.stm|title=Men give DNA in Bible John case|work=[[BBC News]]|date=12 December 2004|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> existed to link McInnes with the murder of Helen Puttock.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dna-tests-clear-bible-john-suspect-1.447304|title=DNA tests clear Bible John suspect|work=The Herald|last=Freeman|first=James|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> [[The Crown]] would officially clear McInnes of any involvement in the Bible John murders in July 1996.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12036852.DNA_tests_clear_Bible_John_suspect/|title=DNA Tests Clear Bible John Suspect|work=Herald Scotland|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Peter Tobin===\nSeveral [[Criminology|criminologists]] and investigators have suggested that convicted serial killer [[Peter Tobin]] may have been Bible John. Tobin was convicted in May 2007 of the 2006 murder of a [[Poles|Polish]] student named Angelika Kluk, who had been raped, beaten, then stabbed to death;<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news|title=I'm Ashamed I Had Sex With Girl, Priest Tells Murder Trial |date=4 April 2007 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1547590/Im-ashamed-I-had-sex-with-girl-priest-tells-murder-trial.html |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> he had relocated from [[Shettleston|Shettleston, Glasgow]]<ref name=\"Herald Scotland\"/> to England in 1969 after marrying his first wife, whom he had met at the Barrowland Ballroom the same year as the murders attributed to Bible John had ended.<ref name=\"Wier\">{{cite book|last=Wier|first=Nigel|year=2012|title=British Serial Killers|publisher=AuthorHouseUK|page=226}}</ref> Tobin would subsequently live in [[Brighton]] for 20 years from 1969,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/jul/12/peter-tobin-serial-killer-brighton-search|title=Peter Tobin's former homes searched in hunt for more victims|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Tran|first=Mark|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/scotland/article6968389.ece|title=Killer question|work=[[The Times]]|date=27 December 2009}}</ref> although from the late 1980s, he would alternately reside in either Scotland or the South of England.<ref name=\"Wilson2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/books/features/a-life-of-crime-professor-david-wilson-trying-to-understand-why-serial-killers-kill-1-816044|title=A life of crime: Professor David Wilson \u2013 trying to understand why serial killers kill|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=4 July 2010|accessdate=26 May 2013}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|A former detective named Joe Jackson (who had investigated the ''Bible John'' murders in the 1960s) has stated that he suspected Tobin may be the perpetrator shortly after he was arrested for Kluk's murder in 2006, adding: \"When I saw his photograph, I thought, 'This is as near to Bible John as you are going to get. This looks a winner.' He fitted the bill in every way, and he had connections with religion.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/exclusive-cops-believe-peter-tobin-1000204|title=Exclusive: Cops believe Peter Tobin was Bible John|work=Daily Record|last=O'Hare|first=Paul|date=3 December 2008|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nTobin had been in his mid-40s when he committed the 1991 murder of two teenage girls whose [[skeletonization|skeletonized]] bodies would subsequently be unearthed from the garden of his home in [[Margate, Kent]] in 2007. He would be convicted of these murders\u2014alongside that of Kluk\u2014between 2007 and 2009. Commencing serial murderous offences of an extremely calculated nature at such an age is unusual\u2014though not unheard of\u2014for a male. Furthermore, the fact that Tobin had attacked Kluk with such violence, then hidden her body before absconding to London prior to his subsequent arrest in addition to the abduction, restraining and concealment known to have been exhibited upon the two 1991 murder victims unearthed from the garden of his Margate home did not suggest the work of an amateur in any of these three cases.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1823130|title=Expert convinced Tobin is Bible John says more murders likely|work=[[The Press and Journal (Scotland)|The Press and Journal]]|last=Lindsay|first=Morag|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nStriking contemporary visual similarities exist between Peter Tobin when aged in his 20s and the 1969 composite drawing of Bible John. In addition, all three of Tobin's former wives have given accounts of being repeatedly imprisoned, throttled, beaten and raped at his hands, and each has stated he had been driven to extreme physical violence by the female [[menstrual cycle]] (a factor long suspected by investigators as being the perpetrator's actual motive behind the murders).<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/> In addition, Tobin is known to have been a staunch [[Roman Catholic]] with strong religious views,<ref name=Wilson/> and the alias Bible John had given to Jean Langford and Helen Puttock in 1969 is similar to one of the [[pseudonym]]s known to have been regularly used by Tobin: John Semple.<ref name=\"Wilson2\"/>\n\nCriminologist [[David Wilson (criminologist)|David Wilson]] actively investigated Tobin's case for three years and strongly believes the available evidence supports his theory that Peter Tobin is Bible John.<ref name=Wilson/> He has stated that the moment he believed Tobin was Bible John occurred during Tobin's trial for the 1991 murder of 18-year-old Dinah McNicol, one of the women whose body had been unearthed from his Margate garden. The [[circumstantial evidence]] which Wilson uses to support this theory includes striking similarities between trial testimony from an acquaintance of Dinah's who had been in her company on the evening of her abduction and the conversation with Bible John that Jean Langford claimed to have had on the evening of her sister's murder; among the important points of overlap are both men mentioning they did not drink at Hogmanay and had a cousin who had once scored a [[hole-in-one]] in a golf match.<ref name=Wilson/> This information\u2014alongside other circumstantial evidence\u2014has led Professor Wilson to state: \"I didn't set out to prove Tobin was Bible John, but I would stake my professional reputation on it.\"<ref name=Wilson/><ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Serial Killer Expert Re-examines the Bible John Murders |date=18 February 2018 |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/16029520.Fifty_years_on__Britain_s_top_serial_killer_expert_re-examines_the_Bible_John_murders/ |work=Herald Scotland |accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Genetic testing|DNA testing]] has been used to clear several suspects, detectives believe obtaining a forensic link between Peter Tobin and any of the murder victims linked to Bible John is unlikely due to the deterioration of the physical samples owing to poor storage.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n'''Operation Anagram'''\n\nAs a result of a police investigation named Operation Anagram, which was initiated in 2006 to trace the movements of Tobin throughout the decades and to determine his potential [[culpability]] in any other crimes, a woman informed investigators she had been raped by Tobin after she had met him at the Barrowland Ballroom in 1968, shortly after the first of the murders known to have been committed by Bible John.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10507524|title=Peter Tobin Crimewatch appeal gets 'massive' response|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=6 July 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Another woman informed investigators in 2010 that she had endured a threatening experience with Tobin at the Barrowland Ballroom, claiming that Tobin had introduced himself as Peter, before pestering her to go with him to a party in the city's Castlemilk area. When this woman viewed pictures of Tobin dating from the late 1960s and early 1970s, she stated: \"[He] was the man who came up to me so many years ago in [the] Barrowlands. I am 100 per cent certain [that] Tobin is Bible John.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/bible-john-asked-me-to-dance---1062823|title=Bible John asked me to dance \u2013 it was Peter Tobin, reveals terrified gran|work=Daily Record|last=Stewart|first=Stephen|date=27 June 2010|accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nNo further murder victims killed in Scotland or elsewhere in the United Kingdom have ever been conclusively attributed to Bible John,{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|pp=207-208}} and the manhunt for this murderer was one of the most extensive manhunts in Scottish criminal history.<ref name=\"DR\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1370421/Bible-John-killer-may-be-unmasked-after-30-years.html|title=Bible John Killer May be Unmasked After 30 Years|work=The Telegraph|last=Booth|first=Jenny|date=15 October 2000|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> The murders of the three women remain unsolved, although the case remains open, with many investigators remaining certain that the perpetrator(s)<ref name=\"Fifty Years On, Britain's Top Seria\"/> of these crimes were highly likely to have been shielded by one or more individuals whom he had known.<ref>''The Hunt Goes On for Bible John. Ultimate Crimes. July 1995 issue. p. 38. ISSN 977-135-85100-2''</ref>\n\nNo uniform consensus that the three killings were actually the work of the same person exists.{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=205}} It has been claimed that the gap of 18 months between the first two killings is unusual for a serial killer, and that the later two murders may have either been copycat killings, or the sole two committed by the same perpetrator. Criticism has also been levelled against the police for potentially hampering their own investigation by prematurely jumping to the conclusion that all three murders had been committed by the same person.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jeffrey|first=Robert|year=2006|title=Crimes Past: Glasgow's Crimes of the Century|publisher=Black and White Publishing}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|[[David Wilson (criminologist)|Professor David Wilson]] has stated that a lapse of time approximating 18 months is not unusual between a serial killer's first and second murders.<ref name=Wilson>{{Cite news|title=Scots murderer Peter Tobin is Bible John, says UK serial killer expert|date=13 June 2010|work=Daily Record|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/scots-murderer-peter-tobin-is-bible-1061592|accessdate=4 March 2019|last=McPherson|first=Lynn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930208&slug=1684320 |title=Serial Killer Says He'd Do It Again |last=Oak Kim |first=Myung |date=8 February 1993 |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |access-date=25 January 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170125214432/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930208&slug=1684320 |archivedate=25 January 2017 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1983, an anonymous individual contacted [[Strathclyde Police]]. This individual claimed to conclusively know that his friend had been Bible John. According to this anonymous individual, both he and his friend had been raised in the [[Cranhill]] district of Glasgow, and both had frequented the Barrowland Ballroom in the 1960s. Allegedly, this individual had read an article in the ''[[Evening Times]]'' five years previously before suddenly realising his friend had been the perpetrator of the murders. The alleged suspect was traced living in [[Netherlands|the Netherlands]], married to a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] woman.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YNdAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nqYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4240,1151385&dq|title=I know it is him|work=Evening Times|last=Hildrey|first=Mike|date=7 February 1983|accessdate=23 May 2013}}</ref> Nothing more was ever heard from the anonymous individual or the reputed suspect.\n\nIn 2004, police announced their intentions to [[genetic testing|genetically test]] a number of men in a further attempt to identify the perpetrator, with all individuals concerned being requested to submit [[Sampling (medicine)#Body fluid sampling|blood samples]].<ref name=\"Men give DNA in Bible John case\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/dna-tests-clear-bible-john-suspect-1.447304|title=DNA tests clear Bible John suspect|work=The Herald|last=Freeman|first=James|date=5 July 1996|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> This endeavour followed the previous discovery of an 80% genetic match from the semen samples retrieved from the final crime scene attributed to Bible John with a DNA sample retrieved at the site of a minor crime committed two years earlier. The sample was enough of a match to lead officers to believe that the person who committed the offence was related to the killer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/DNA+BREAKTHROUGH%3A+POLICE+TRACE+FAMILY+OF+BIBLE+JOHN+SERIAL+KILLER.-a0126288448|title=DNA breakthrough: police trace family of Bible John serial killer|publisher=The Free Library|website=Sunday Mail|last=Lavery|first=Charles|date=19 December 2004|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe sole witness ever to have engaged in a lengthy conversation with Bible John, Jean Langford, died in September 2010 at the age of 74.<ref name=Findlay>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/2010/09/26/hunt-for-bible-john-comes-to-an-end-after-only-witness-in-case-dies-86908-22588146/|title=Hunt for Bible John comes to an end after only witness in case dies|date=26 September 2010|accessdate=4 March 2019|work=Daily Record|last=Findlay|first=Russell}}</ref> Langford had given police the description used to form the second composite drawing created of the suspect, which continues to remain the most significant clue as to the perpetrator's physical appearance. Despite Professor Wilson's assertion that Peter Tobin may have been Bible John, when Jean Langford discussed her sister's murderer many decades later, she dismissed this theory, stating emphatically that Tobin had not been the man with whom she had shared a taxi on the night of her sister's murder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whelan|first1=Michael|title=Bible John - Unresolved|url=https://unresolved.me/bible-john/|website=unresolved.me|accessdate=11 July 2018|date=21 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE SOUTH PARK OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n=== Books ===\n* {{Cite book|last= Harrison|first= Paul|title= Dancing with the Devil: The Bible John Murders|year= 2013|publisher= Vertical Editions|location= Skipton|isbn= 978-1-904-09173-8}}.\n* {{Cite book|last=Malloy|first=Andrew D.|title=Bible John - Closure|year= 2011|publisher= Pneuma Springs Publishing|location= Kent|isbn= 978-1-907-72816-7}}.\n* {{cite book| last = Stoddart| first = Charles| title = Bible John: Search for a Sadist|year = 1980| publisher = Paul Harris Publishing | location = Edinburgh| isbn = 978-0-904-50589-4}}.\n* {{cite book| last1 = Wilson| first1 = David| last2 = Harrison| first2 = Paul| title = The Lost British Serial Killer| year = 2010| publisher = Brown Book Group Limited | location = London| isbn = 978-0-751-54232-5}}\n\n=== Television ===\n* The [[BBC]] has broadcast a 30-minute documentary focusing upon the murders committed by Bible John. Presented by Hugh Cochrane, this episode was screened on 18 September 1970, and concluded with a direct quote from [[Jeremiah]], Chapter 23, Verse 24, appealing to the perpetrator to hand himself in to the police: 'Can any hide himself in secret places, that I shall not see him? saith the Lord?{{sfn|Lloyd|1986|p=204}}\n* [[STV (TV channel)|STV]] have broadcast a 45-minute documentary focusing upon the murders committed by Bible John. This documentary, titled ''In Search of Bible John'', was initially broadcast in 2011, and explores the possibility Peter Tobin may have been the perpetrator of the three murders.\n* The case of Bible John featured in a December 2005 episode of ''[[Unsolved (UK TV programme)|Unsolved]].'' Narrated by [[Alex Norton]], the program primarily focuses on the death of the final victim, Helen Puttock, and includes interviews with Puttock's husband.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taggart actor steps in to try to solve Bible John murder riddle |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/taggart-actor-steps-in-to-try-to-solve-bible-john-murder-riddle-1-1096054/amp |accessdate=27 January 2019 |work=The Scotsman |date=17 September 2005}}</ref>\n<!---PLEASE DO NOT ADD SONG REFERENCES, REFERENCES TO INCIDENTAL DEPICTIONS UPON ALBUM COVERS OR OTHER DEPICTIONS UPON TV SHOWS LIKE THE SIMPSONS OR OTHER IRRELEVANT TRIVIA HERE. IT DOES NOT BELONG HERE AND WILL REMOVED WITH NO FURTHER DISCUSSION. TRIVIA IS INAPPROPRIATE PER THE PROJECT GOVERNING THIS ARTICLE.--->\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Capital punishment in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of serial killers by number of victims|List of murderers by number of victims]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[List of serial killers by country]]\n* [[Unsolved murders in the United Kingdom]]\n{{col-end}}\n{{Portal bar|1960s|Law|Scotland|United Kingdom}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Cited works and further reading==\n* {{Cite book|last= Cawthorne|first= Nigel|title=The Mammoth Book of Killers at Large|year= 2007|publisher=Constable & Robinson Ltd|location= London|isbn= 978-1-845-29631-5}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Harrison|first= Paul|title=Dancing with the Devil: The Bible John Murders|year= 2013|publisher= Vertical Editions|location= Skipton|isbn= 978-1-904-09173-8}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Lane|first= Brian|last2= Gregg|first2= Wilfred|title= The Encyclopedia Of Serial Killers|origyear= 1992|year= 1995|publisher= Berkley Books|location= New York City|isbn= 0-425-15213-8|ref= harv|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofse00lane}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Lloyd|first= Georgina|title= One Was Not Enough: True Stories of Multiple Murderers|year= 1986|publisher= Bantam Books|location= London|isbn= 978-0-553-17605-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Malloy|first=Andrew D.|title=Bible John - Closure|year= 2011|publisher= Pneuma Springs Publishing|location= Kent|isbn= 978-1-907-72816-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Newton| first = Michael| title = The Encyclopedia of Unsolved Crimes|year = 2004| publisher = Facts on File | location = New York| isbn = 978-0-816-07818-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Stoddart| first = Charles| title = Bible John: Search for a Sadist|year = 1980| publisher = Paul Harris Publishing | location = Edinburgh| isbn = 978-0-904-50589-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Whittington-Egan| first = Molly| title = Scottish Murder Stories|year = 1998| publisher = Neil Wilson Publishing Ltd.| location = Glasgow| isbn = 978-1-906-47647-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last= Whittington-Egan|first= Richard|last2= Whittington-Egan|first2= Molly|title= The Murder Almanac|year= 1992|publisher= Neil Wilson Publishing Ltd.|location= Glasgow|isbn= 978-1-897-78404-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last1 = Wilson| first1 = Colin| last2 = Wilson| first2 = Damon| last3 = Wilson| first3 = Rowan| title = World Famous Murders| year = 1993| publisher = Parragon Publishing| location = London| isbn = 978-0-752-50122-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* 2000 ''[[BBC News]]'' account detailing [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/971771.stm contemporary developments] pertaining to leads in the Bible John inquiry\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051104053053/http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/unsolved/bible_john/index.html Bible John] at Court TV's ''Crime Library''\n* [https://www.historicmysteries.com/bible-john/ Bible John] at ''historicmysteries.com''\n* [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=GGgVawPscysC&dat=19691101&printsec=frontpage&hl=en Contemporary edition] of ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Glasgow Herald]]'', focusing upon the discovery of the body of Helen Puttock (p.&nbsp;1)\n* [https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/news/history/bible-john-killing-glasgow-barrowlands-11533797 ''glasgowlive.co.uk''] article pertaining to Bible John\n* International Crime Writing Festival [https://bloodyscotland.com/events/who-was-bible-john/ article focusing upon the Bible John murders]\n* [https://www.trace-evidence.com/008/ ''The Bible John Murders''] at trace-evidence.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John, Bible}}\n[[Category:1968 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1969 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1960s in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:1968 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:1969 in Scotland]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish criminals]]\n[[Category:History of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Murder in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Murder in Scotland]]\n[[Category:People associated with Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish rapists]]\n[[Category:Scottish serial 